ivision]]\n|[[David Crane (programmer)|David Crane]]\n|{{dts|1981-07}}\n|{{sort|1|1,000,000}}\n|align=\"center\"|<ref name=\"jameslevy\"/>\n|-\n|''[[Kaboom! (video game)|Kaboom!]]''\n|[[Activision]]\n|[[Activision]]\n|[[Larry Kaplan]]\n|{{dts|1981-07}}\n|{{sort|1|1,000,000}}\n|align=\"center\"|<ref name=\"jameslevy\"/>\n|-\n|''[[Yars' Revenge]]''\n|[[Atari, Inc.]]\n|[[Atari, Inc.]]\n|[[Howard Scott Warshaw]]\n|{{dts|1982-05}}\n|{{sort|1|1,000,000}}\n|align=\"center\"|<ref name=\"warshaw\">{{cite web |url=http://www.digitpress.com/library/interviews/interview_howard_scott_warshaw.html |title=DP Interviews... Howard Scott Warshaw |last=Stilphen |first=Scott |publisher=Digital Press |accessdate=April 22, 2017 }}</ref>\n|-\n|''[[Atlantis (video game)|Atlantis]]''\n|[[Imagic]]\n|[[Imagic]]\n|Dennis Koble\n|{{dts|1982-07}}\n|{{sort|1|1,000,000}}\n|align=\"center\"|<ref name=\"ign\"/>\n|-\n|''[[Star Wars: The Empire Strikes Back (1982 video game)|Star Wars: The Empire Strikes Back]]''\n|[[Parker Brothers]]\n|[[Parker Brothers]]\n|Rex Bradford\n|{{dts|1982-07}}\n|{{sort|1|1,000,000}}\n|align=\"center\"|<ref name=\"parker\"/>{{Additional citation needed|date=January 2019|reason=I could not find any information about the number of units sold}}\n|-\n|''[[Cosmic Ark]]''\n|[[Imagic]]\n|[[Imagic]]\n|[[Rob Fulop]]\n|{{dts|1982-08}}\n|{{sort|1|1,000,000}}\n|align=\"center\"|<ref name=\"robfulop\"/>\n|-\n|''[[Megamania]]''\n|[[Activision]]\n|[[Activision]]\n|[[Steve Cartwright]]\n|{{dts|1982-10}}\n|{{sort|1|1,000,000}}\n|align=\"center\"|<ref name=\"ign\"/>\n|-\n|''[[Raiders of the Lost Ark (video game)|Raiders of the Lost Ark]]''\n|[[Atari, Inc.]]\n|[[Atari, Inc.]]\n|[[Howard Scott Warshaw]]\n|{{dts|1982-11}}\n|{{sort|1|1,000,000}}\n|align=\"center\"|<ref name=\"warshaw\"/>\n|-\n|''[[River Raid]]''\n|[[Activision]]\n|[[Activision]]\n|[[Carol Shaw (video game designer)|Carol Shaw]]\n|{{dts|1982-12}}\n|{{sort|1|1,000,000}}\n|align=\"center\"|<ref name=\"jameslevy\"/>\n|}\n</onlyinclude>\n\n==See also==\n*[[List of best-selling video games]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/19991111030208/http://gtinteractive.com/ Atari official website]\n\n{{vgbestsellers}}\n\n[[Category:Lists of best-selling video games|Atari 2600]]\n[[Category:Atari 2600 games|*]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Wikipedia list article}}\n[[File:Atari-2600-Wood-4Sw-Set.jpg|thumb|250px|Atari 2600 four-switch \"wood veneer\" model]]\nThe best-selling [[video game]] of all-time on the [[Atari 2600]] console is ''[[Pac-Man (1982 video game)|Pac-Man]]'', a port of the [[Pac-Man|arcade game of the same name]] programmed by [[Tod Frye]].<ref name=\"ign\">{{cite web |url=http://www.ign.com/articles/2008/08/26/top-10-best-selling-atari-2600-games |title=Top 10 Best-Selling Atari 2600 Games |last=Buchanan |first=Levi |work=[[IGN]] |publisher=[[Ziff Davis]] |date=August 26, 2008 |accessdate=April 22, 2017 }}</ref> Originally created by [[Toru Iwatani]] and released in 1980, ''Pac-Man'' was later ported to many home video game consoles, beginning with the Atari 2600 in 1982.<ref name=\"egm1982\">{{cite magazine |last=Katz |first=Arnie |last2=Kunkel |first2=Bill |author-link2=Bill Kunkel (gaming) |date=May 1982 |title=The A-Maze-ing World of Gobble Games: A Guide to Maze-Chase Gamers |url=https://archive.org/stream/electronic-games-magazine-1982-05/Electronic_Games_Issue_03_Vol_01_03_1982_May#page/n61/mode/2up |magazine=[[Electronic Games]] |location=New York City, New York |publisher=Reese Publishing Company |volume=1 |issue=3 |pages=62\u201363 |access-date=April 22, 2017 }}</ref> Within months it became the best-selling home video game of all-time, with more than 1.5 million units pre-ordered by customers before its release.<ref name=\"egm1982\"/> ''Pac-Man'' went on to sell over 7.7 million units worldwide.<ref name=\"businessisfun\">{{cite book |last=Goldberg |first=Marty |last2=Vendel |first2=Curt |date=November 25, 2012 |title=Atari Inc.: Business Is Fun |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=3FwGMtRafrAC&pg=PA582&lpg=PA582#v=onepage&q&f=false |location=Carmel, New York |publisher=Syzygy Press |page=582 |isbn=978-0-9855974-0-5 |access-date=April 22, 2017 }}</ref> The second best-selling Atari 2600 game is ''[[Pitfall!]]'', designed by [[David Crane (programmer)|David Crane]] for [[Activision]], which has sold over 4 million units.<ref name=\"pitfall\">{{cite news |url=https://www.wired.com/2010/01/david-crane-pioneer/ |title=Pitfall! Creator David Crane Is Named Videogame Pioneer |last=Kohler |first=Chris |work=[[Wired (magazine)|Wired]] |publisher=[[Cond\u00e9 Nast]] |date=January 26, 2010 |accessdate=April 22, 2017 }}</ref>\n\nOf the top 22 best-selling Atari 2600 video games, ten were developed and/or published by the console's manufacturer, [[Atari, Inc.]] Other publishers with multiple entries in the top 20 are Activision (six titles), [[Imagic]] (three titles) and [[Parker Brothers]] (two titles). Three of the games in the top 20 were programmed by [[David Crane (programmer)|David Crane]], three by [[Howard Scott Warshaw]], three by [[Rob Fulop]], and two by Bradley G. Stewart. The Atari 2600 port of ''[[Space Invaders]]'', programmed by Rick Maurer for [[Taito]], was the first video game to sell a million copies,<ref>{{cite book |last=Weiss |first=Bret |date=July 6, 2007 |title=Classic Home Video Games, 1972\u20131984: A Complete Reference Guide |location=Jefferson, North Carolina |publisher=[[McFarland & Company]] |page=108 |isbn=978-0-7864322-6-4 }}</ref> while the console port of ''[[Asteroids (video game)|Asteroids]]'' was the best-selling video game prior to the release of ''Pac-Man''.<ref name=\"businessisfun\"/>\n\n==Video games==\n<onlyinclude>\n{|class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders sortable\"\n|+ List of best-selling video games on the Atari 2600\n!scope=\"col\"|Title\n!scope=\"col\"|Developer(s)\n!scope=\"col\"|Publisher(s)\n!scope=\"col\"|Programmer(s)\n!scope=\"col\"|