{"title_page": "Paul French (author)", "text_new": "{{autobiography|date=June 2017}}\n{{sources|date=October 2018}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2017}}\n{{Use British English|date=February 2017}}\n'''Paul French''' (born 27 August 1966) is a British author. In addition to articles about a range of subjects, he has specialised in books about modern Chinese history and contemporary Chinese society, including ''[[Midnight in Peking]]''. Stated that scientists should circumvent oppressive Chinese government to search origins of COVID\n\n==Biography==\n\nFrench was born in the [[London Borough of Enfield]]. He attended Raglan Junior School and [[Edmonton County School]], North London. He gained an M.Phil from the [[University of Glasgow]] and studied Chinese at the [[City Literary Institute]]. After university French worked briefly for ''[[Time Out (magazine)|Time Out]]'' magazine and ''Euromonitor'' in London before relocating to [[Shanghai]]. There he co-founded the independent research firm Access Asia. It specialises in analysing Chinese consumer and retail markets. In September 2011 Access Asia was acquired by the London-based market research company [[Mintel]]. French is now a full-time author based in London.\n\n==Journalism and publishing==\n\nFrench was columnist for the ''China Economic Quarterly'' and the ''[[China Economic Review]]'' as well as being a columnist for and the China Editor of ''Ethical Corporation'' magazine. French has contributed to ''[[Foreign Policy]]'', ''[[The Washington Post]]'', ''[[South China Morning Post]]'', ''[[Shanghai Daily]]'', ''[[The Guardian]]'', ''The Cleaver Quarterly'' and ''[[The Diplomat]]''.\n\nFrench is a contributor to the UK's ''[[Real Crime]]'' magazine.  In CNN article suggested scientists should circumvent oppressive Chinese government for truth on COVID origins.  \n\nAs a book reviewer, French has contributed to the (British) ''[[Literary Review]]'', ''[[The Washington Post]]'', ''The Asian Review of Books'', and the ''[[Los Angeles Review of Books]]''. He is the author of the fortnightly \"Crime and the City\" column for ''[[Literary Hub]]''. French has also made literary contributions to the ''[[Asia Literary Review]]'' and ''[[Cha: An Asian Literary Journal]]''.\n\nHe is also a former board member of the Shanghai Foreign Correspondents Club and a member of the Korea Research Hub (KRH) based within Leeds and Sheffield universities. French was also a member of the editorial advisory board for Anthem Press's \u2018China in the Twenty First Century\u2019 series and the Honorary Research and Publications Director for the [[Royal Asiatic Society of Great Britain and Ireland]] \u2013 China Branch. In 2011 French launched the Asian Arguments series of books for [[Zed Books]]acting as the Series Editor.\n\nFrench is also the author of the blog ''[http://www.chinarhyming.com/ China Rhyming: A gallimaufry of random China history and research interests]''.\n\n==''Midnight in Peking''==\n\n''[[Midnight in Peking]]'' (2012) is French's most commercially successful title. It has appeared on numerous best-seller lists around the world and won several awards:{{citation needed|date=October 2018}}\n* 2013 [[Mystery Writers of America]] [[Edgar Award]] in the Best Fact Crime category\n* 2013 [[Crime Writers' Association]] [[CWA Gold Dagger for Non-Fiction]]\n* 2012 Australian Book Industry Awards \u2013 International Success of the Year\n* nominated for the 2013 [[Macavity Awards]] \u2013 Best Mystery Non-Fiction\n\n''[[Midnight in Peking]]'' was also a [[BBC Radio 4]] [[Book of the Week]].\n\n===Co-authored works===\n\n*''One Billion Shoppers: Accessing Asia's Consuming Passions After the Meltdown'' (Nicholas Brealey Publishing, 1998) \u2013 with Matthew Crabbe\n*''Oil on Water: Tankers, Pirates and the Rise of China'' (Zed Books, 2010) \u2013 with Sam Chambers\n*''Fat China: How Expanding Waistlines are Changing a Nation'' (Anthem Press, 2010) \u2013 with Matthew Crabbe\n\n===Sole-authored works===\n\n*''North Korea The Paranoid Peninsula: A Modern History'' (Zed Books, 2005 \u2013 updated edition, 2007)\n*''Carl Crow: A Tough Old China Hand \u2013 The Life, Times and Adventures of an American in Shanghai'' (Hong Kong University Press, 2006)\n*''Through the Looking Glass: China Foreign Journalists From Opium War to Mao'' (Hong Kong University Press, 2009)\n*''The Old Shanghai A-Z'' (Hong Kong University Press, 2010)\n*''Midnight in Peking: How the Murder of a Young Englishwoman Haunted the Last Days of Old China'' (Beijing: Viking, 2011; London: Viking, 2012; New York: Penguin Books, Rev., 2012). {{ISBN|9780143121008}}.\n*''The Badlands: Decadent Playground of Old Peking'' (Asia and Australia: Penguin Specials, 2012; London, New York: Penguin Specials, 2013)\n*''North Korea: State of Paranoia'' (London: Zed Books, 2014).  {{ISBN|9781780329475}}.\n*''City of Devils: A Shanghai Noir'' (London: riverrun, 2018; New York: Picador, 2018). {{ISBN|9781787470330}}.\n\n== References ==\n<!--- See http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wikipedia:Footnotes on how to create references using <ref></ref> tags which will then appear here automatically -->\n<references />\n*\"[https://web.archive.org/web/20110928054802/http://www.mwf.com.au/2011/?name=Writer-French-Paul Paul French]\". Melbourne Writers Festival.\n*\"[http://www.penguin.com.au/contributors/6638/paul-french Paul French]\". Penguin Books Australia.\n*\"[http://blog.booktopia.com.au/2011/08/11/paul-french-author-of-midnight-in-peking-answers-ten-terrifying-questions/ Paul French, author of Midnight in Peking, answers Ten Terrifying Questions]\". Booktopia Blog. 11 August 2011.\n\n== External links ==\n* [http://www.midnightinpeking.com/ Midnight in Peking website]\n* [http://www.chinarhyming.com/ China Rhyming]\n* Jonathan Spence, [http://www.nybooks.com/articles/archives/2013/mar/21/who-killed-pamela-peking/ \"Who Killed Pamela in Peking?\"] (Review of ''Midnight in Peking''), ''New York Review of Books'' 21 March 2013.\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:French, Paul}}\n<!--- Categories --->\n[[Category:1966 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Alumni of the University of Glasgow]]\n[[Category:British historians]]\n[[Category:People from the London Borough of Enfield]]\n", "text_old": "{{autobiography|date=June 2017}}\n{{sources|date=October 2018}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2017}}\n{{Use British English|date=February 2017}}\n'''Paul French''' (born 27 August 1966) is a British author. In addition to articles about a range of subjects, he has specialised in books about modern Chinese history and contemporary Chinese society, including ''[[Midnight in Peking]]''.\n\n==Biography==\n\nFrench was born in the [[London Borough of Enfield]]. He attended Raglan Junior School and [[Edmonton County School]], North London. He gained an M.Phil from the [[University of Glasgow]] and studied Chinese at the [[City Literary Institute]]. After university French worked briefly for ''[[Time Out (magazine)|Time Out]]'' magazine and ''Euromonitor'' in London before relocating to [[Shanghai]]. There he co-founded the independent research firm Access Asia. It specialises in analysing Chinese consumer and retail markets. In September 2011 Access Asia was acquired by the London-based market research company [[Mintel]]. French is now a full-time author based in London.\n\n==Journalism and publishing==\n\nFrench was columnist for the ''China Economic Quarterly'' and the ''[[China Economic Review]]'' as well as being a columnist for and the China Editor of ''Ethical Corporation'' magazine. French has contributed to ''[[Foreign Policy]]'', ''[[The Washington Post]]'', ''[[South China Morning Post]]'', ''[[Shanghai Daily]]'', ''[[The Guardian]]'', ''The Cleaver Quarterly'' and ''[[The Diplomat]]''.\n\nFrench is a contributor to the UK's ''[[Real Crime]]'' magazine.\n\nAs a book reviewer, French has contributed to the (British) ''[[Literary Review]]'', ''[[The Washington Post]]'', ''The Asian Review of Books'', and the ''[[Los Angeles Review of Books]]''. He is the author of the fortnightly \"Crime and the City\" column for ''[[Literary Hub]]''. French has also made literary contributions to the ''[[Asia Literary Review]]'' and ''[[Cha: An Asian Literary Journal]]''.\n\nHe is also a former board member of the Shanghai Foreign Correspondents Club and a member of the Korea Research Hub (KRH) based within Leeds and Sheffield universities. French was also a member of the editorial advisory board for Anthem Press's \u2018China in the Twenty First Century\u2019 series and the Honorary Research and Publications Director for the [[Royal Asiatic Society of Great Britain and Ireland]] \u2013 China Branch. In 2011 French launched the Asian Arguments series of books for [[Zed Books]]acting as the Series Editor.\n\nFrench is also the author of the blog ''[http://www.chinarhyming.com/ China Rhyming: A gallimaufry of random China history and research interests]''.\n\n==''Midnight in Peking''==\n\n''[[Midnight in Peking]]'' (2012) is French's most commercially successful title. It has appeared on numerous best-seller lists around the world and won several awards:{{citation needed|date=October 2018}}\n* 2013 [[Mystery Writers of America]] [[Edgar Award]] in the Best Fact Crime category\n* 2013 [[Crime Writers' Association]] [[CWA Gold Dagger for Non-Fiction]]\n* 2012 Australian Book Industry Awards \u2013 International Success of the Year\n* nominated for the 2013 [[Macavity Awards]] \u2013 Best Mystery Non-Fiction\n\n''[[Midnight in Peking]]'' was also a [[BBC Radio 4]] [[Book of the Week]].\n\n===Co-authored works===\n\n*''One Billion Shoppers: Accessing Asia's Consuming Passions After the Meltdown'' (Nicholas Brealey Publishing, 1998) \u2013 with Matthew Crabbe\n*''Oil on Water: Tankers, Pirates and the Rise of China'' (Zed Books, 2010) \u2013 with Sam Chambers\n*''Fat China: How Expanding Waistlines are Changing a Nation'' (Anthem Press, 2010) \u2013 with Matthew Crabbe\n\n===Sole-authored works===\n\n*''North Korea The Paranoid Peninsula: A Modern History'' (Zed Books, 2005 \u2013 updated edition, 2007)\n*''Carl Crow: A Tough Old China Hand \u2013 The Life, Times and Adventures of an American in Shanghai'' (Hong Kong University Press, 2006)\n*''Through the Looking Glass: China Foreign Journalists From Opium War to Mao'' (Hong Kong University Press, 2009)\n*''The Old Shanghai A-Z'' (Hong Kong University Press, 2010)\n*''Midnight in Peking: How the Murder of a Young Englishwoman Haunted the Last Days of Old China'' (Beijing: Viking, 2011; London: Viking, 2012; New York: Penguin Books, Rev., 2012). {{ISBN|9780143121008}}.\n*''The Badlands: Decadent Playground of Old Peking'' (Asia and Australia: Penguin Specials, 2012; London, New York: Penguin Specials, 2013)\n*''North Korea: State of Paranoia'' (London: Zed Books, 2014).  {{ISBN|9781780329475}}.\n*''City of Devils: A Shanghai Noir'' (London: riverrun, 2018; New York: Picador, 2018). {{ISBN|9781787470330}}.\n\n== References ==\n<!--- See http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wikipedia:Footnotes on how to create references using <ref></ref> tags which will then appear here automatically -->\n<references />\n*\"[https://web.archive.org/web/20110928054802/http://www.mwf.com.au/2011/?name=Writer-French-Paul Paul French]\". Melbourne Writers Festival.\n*\"[http://www.penguin.com.au/contributors/6638/paul-french Paul French]\". Penguin Books Australia.\n*\"[http://blog.booktopia.com.au/2011/08/11/paul-french-author-of-midnight-in-peking-answers-ten-terrifying-questions/ Paul French, author of Midnight in Peking, answers Ten Terrifying Questions]\". Booktopia Blog. 11 August 2011.\n\n== External links ==\n* [http://www.midnightinpeking.com/ Midnight in Peking website]\n* [http://www.chinarhyming.com/ China Rhyming]\n* Jonathan Spence, [http://www.nybooks.com/articles/archives/2013/mar/21/who-killed-pamela-peking/ \"Who Killed Pamela in Peking?\"] (Review of ''Midnight in Peking''), ''New York Review of Books'' 21 March 2013.\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:French, Paul}}\n<!--- Categories --->\n[[Category:1966 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Alumni of the University of Glasgow]]\n[[Category:British historians]]\n[[Category:People from the London Borough of Enfield]]\n", "name_user": "100.16.56.68", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Paul_French_(author)"}
{"title_page": "Dead Dog Beach", "text_new": "{{short description|Beach in Yabucoa, Puerto Rico}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=December 2019}}\n\n'''Dead Dog Beach''', also known as '''Sato Beach''' and officially named '''Playa Lucia''', is a beach within the municipality of [[Yabucoa]] in southeastern [[Puerto Rico]]. Its \"Dead Dog Beach\" came because it is the dumping ground for stray animals, mainly dogs that the inhabitants of Yabucoa can no longer afford. Most are not [[spayed]] or [[neutered]]; in [[Puerto Rican culture]], cutting a dog's \"manhood\" is seen as inappropriate/cruel. The strays [[breed]] uncontrollably, giving rise to more homeless dogs.\n\nDead Dog Beach was known for one of the highest concentrations of stray animals in the country. It attracted [[animal rights activist]]s and groups hoping to make a difference. One example is The Sato Project, a large-scale [[rescue]] project focusing its efforts on Sato Beach/Yabucoa.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thesatoproject.org/|title=The Sato Project|website=The Sato Project|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-26}}</ref> Many individuals who come are so moved by these animals' living conditions that they extend their stay and help. Various rescue projects focus on the island's development. Many of these efforts were prompted by abuse of animals, even by local authorities, as in the Barceloneta Massacre in 2007.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cbsnews.com/news/more-than-50-pets-massacred-in-puerto-rico/|title=More Than 50 Pets Massacred In Puerto Rico|website=www.cbsnews.com|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-26}}</ref>\n\n== Geography and climate ==\n[[Puerto Rico]], mainly a 90-by-30 mile island located in the [[Caribbean]] region, includes smaller islands off of its eastern coast. Its average temperatures range from 70-80 degrees [[Fahrenheit]]. Its beaches stretch for hundreds of miles.<ref>Barreto, Maritza (2017). Assessment of beach morphology at Puerto Rico Island. Puerto Rico and Caribbean Beach Network. retrieved from: http://drna.pr.gov/wp-content/uploads/2017/05/Geomorphic-Assessment-of-Puerto-Rico-1977-to-2016.pdf</ref> Along the northern coasts, are cliffs and a region known as the [[Karst]] region. This region contains notable land features such as caves, caverns, waterfalls, underground rivers and rain forests. Puerto Rico has the largest and deepest trench in the [[Atlantic Ocean]], known as the [[Puerto Rico Trench]].<ref name=Landforms>{{Cite web|url=http://www.worldatlas.com/webimage/countrys/namerica/caribb/puertorico/prland.htm|title=Geography of Puerto Rico, Landforms - World Atlas|website=www.worldatlas.com|access-date=2016-11-14}}</ref> Notable rivers include the [[Guayan\u00e9s River (Yabucoa, Puerto Rico)|Guayanes River]] extends for 17 miles, as well as the [[Prieto River (Ponce, Puerto Rico)|Prieto]], [[Arenas River (Yabucoa, Puerto Rico)|Arenas]], [[Limones River|Limones]] and [[Ingenio River|Ingenio Rivers]].<ref name=enciclopediapr>{{Cite web|url=http://www.enciclopediapr.org/ing/article.cfm?ref=09052002|title=Municipalities: Yabucoa|website=www.enciclopediapr.org|access-date=2016-11-07}}</ref>\n\nYabucoa is surrounded on three sides by the San Lorenzo Batholith and the Caribbean Sea. It is [[humid]] and mainly flat. Mountain ranges in this area include Santa Elena peak, Pandura, and the Cayey Range.  Yabucoa valley consists mainly of farmland. It was originally a small mountain town.<ref name=enciclopediapr/>\n\n== History ==\nThe name [[Yabucoa, Puerto Rico|Yubucoa]] means \"place or site with waters\", although some scholars believe it means \"place of cassava\".<ref name=enciclopediapr/> The area was founded in 1793 when Manuel Col\u00f3n de Bonillas and his wife, Catalina Morales Pacheco, donated the settlement.<ref name=enciclopediapr/> [[Puerto Rico]] was a [[Spanish colony]] until 1898, when it became a U.S. territory.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cia.gov/library/publications/the-world-factbook/geos/rq.html|title=Central America :: Puerto Rico \u2014 The World Factbook - Central Intelligence Agency|website=www.cia.gov|access-date=2020-03-25}}</ref> Economic hardship dates back to the 17th and 18th centuries. Although briefly resolved, such hardships play a key role in the story of Dead Dog Beach. Yabucoa received popularity when in 1989 the [[WBO]] held a boxing championship there between [[Orlando Fernandez]] and [[Julio Gervacio]]. Fernandez' victory brought attention to the town and to Puerto Rico.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.fightsrec.com/orlando-fernandez.html|title=Orlando Fernandez boxer|website=www.fightsrec.com|access-date=2016-11-07}}</ref>\n\nBefore becoming known as \"Dead Dog Beach,\" Playa Lucia was once a popular beach. It consisted of a pool, cabana facilities and other recreational activities. It became a wasteland: the pool was covered in graffiti, and full of garbage. The facilities were abandoned and without proper maintenance turned into ruins. The only visitors who roamed the area were dogs and cats among the piles of pet carcasses.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.cnn.com/2015/08/25/living/sato-project-dead-dog-beach-puerto-rico/index.html|title=Sato Project saves pups from 'Dead Dog Beach'|author=Ann Roche and Evelio Contreras|website=CNN|access-date=2016-11-14}}</ref> As of 2014, a gate was put up to deny access to people who would dump dogs on the beach and [[Sato Project]] has been regularly monitoring the beach for strays.<ref name=\"stitcher\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.stitcher.com/s?eid=41157978|title=Hope For The Lost And Abandoned Dogs Of Puerto Rico from The Animal House &#124; WAMU 88.5|website=www.stitcher.com}}</ref><ref name=\"thesatoproject\">{{cite web|url=https://www.thesatoproject.org/spayathon|title=The Spayathon for Puerto Rico|website=The Sato Project|accessdate=2020-03-14}}</ref>\n\n== Causes  ==\n\n=== Economy ===\nThe [[Economy of Puerto Rico#Finance|economy of Puerto Rico]] weakened under the weight of the 2017 [[Puerto Rico#Hurricanes Irma and Maria|hurricanes]]. Many individuals were forced to abandon their pets. Local [[Animal shelter|shelter]]s filled and individuals left the island.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://money.cnn.com/2016/03/20/news/economy/puerto-rico-crisis-stray-dogs/index.html|title=Puerto Rico has become 'dead dog island'|last=Long|first=Heather|date=2016-03-20|website=CNNMoney|access-date=2016-11-14}}</ref>\n\n=== Culture ===\nThe practice of not spaying and neutering pets causes population to expand rapidly. A majority of Puerto Rican pet owners believe that it sterilization is not \"natural\" and/or \"kills their sex life\". Other owners breed their animals as a source of income. Some individuals go so far as to argue that it is less humane to kill their pet's \"sex lives\" than to actually kill the pet.<ref>{{Citation|via=DrunkenGunsAndBombs on YouTube|title=100,000|first=Juan Agust\u00edn|last=M\u00e1rquez|date=2012-09-07|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=yWkXtxXq84M|accessdate=2016-11-14}}</ref>\n\n== Rescue projects ==\n\n=== SATO Project ===\nThe Sato Project is an animal rescue project that operates across the territory while mainly focusing on Dead Dog Beach. Launched in 2011 by Chrissy Beckles and her husband Bobby Beckles, it is the official rescue group in Yabucoa. The Sato Project is composed of two teams: one within Puerto Rico and another in the United States. These teams work together to ship the dogs to the U.S.\n\nThe process of helping these animals begins with logging and identifying them on the beach. Once logged, the Beach Coordinator checks on the animals and provides food and medicine until shelter space becomes available. Shelter dogs receive a full [[check-up]]: a [[veterinarian]] provides any necessary care. In addition to a check-up, the dogs are also spayed/neutered and [[vaccinate]]d. When the dog is well enough to travel, volunteers in Puerto Rico prepare it to fly to either [[JFK Airport|JFK]] or [[Newark Airport]]<nowiki/>s. Upon arrival the dogs are transported by another team of volunteers to the project's adoption team. The latter works to find every dog a home. They will take dogs back upon an owner's request.<ref name=\"What We Do\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.thesatoproject.org/what-we-do/|title=What We Do|website=The Sato Project|access-date=2016-11-14}}</ref>\n\n==== Spay and neuter campaign ====\nThe Sato Project began a multi-phase campaign to facilitate and promote free spaying and neutering events in the area. The first major phase started in 2015 when local government agreed to put up cameras and a gated fence on the beach. This fence is meant to keep people from releasing animals there or abusing the current animal population after hours.\n\nThe second phase was set to start in March 2016. It was to include three parts:\n\n* Team with the [[Humane Society International]] to hold ten spay, neuter, and [[microchipping]] clinics throughout Yabucoa\n* Target low income neighborhoods to provide pet owners with 30 free vouchers per month for access to free spaying, neutering, and microchipping at veterinary clinics in Yabucoa. \n* Fight the [[overpopulation]] and current conditions by involving the community with the goal of helping at least 30 dogs per month.<ref name=\"What We Do\" />\n\n=== Other rescue operations ===\nThe [[Animal Rescue Foundation]] is an animal rescue project started in 1997 which primarily operates in [[Rinc\u00f3n, Puerto Rico|Rincon]]. Its main focus is to rescue dogs and cats, provide spaying/neutering and adoption services, and to educate the community about pet safety.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://arfrincon.org/about-arf/|title=Animal Rescue Foundations|last=|first=|date=|website=|publisher=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\nBarks For Hope is a rescue foundation started by Leo Roubian in 2014. Its primary goal is to provide aid and adoption for abandoned animals throughout the island. The operation offers transportation and medical care, including rehabilitation and rides to be spayed and neutered.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.barksofhope.org/|title=Barks for Hope|last=|first=|date=|website=|publisher=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\n==== Individual rescue efforts ====\nStephen McGarva moved to Puerto Rico in 2005, and, while exploring his new home, came face-to-face with the animals' plight. McGarva began feeding the dogs and cleaning their [[wound]]s daily, in the hope that it would help make them more adoptable. McGarva remained in the territory for several years to take care of the animals before returning the U.S. where by sharing his experiences, raised awareness of the animal crisis in Puerto Rico.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://nypost.com/2014/08/24/hundreds-of-dogs-saved-from-massacre-on-puerto-rico/|title=Hundreds of dogs saved from massacre on Puerto Rico|last=Buiso|first=Gary|date=2014-08-24|website=New York Post|language=en|access-date=2020-03-25}}</ref>\n\n== Barceloneta massacre ==\nIn fall 2007, Puerto Rican animal control captured dozens of dogs and cats from housing projects around Barceloneta and allegedly threw them off a bridge to their deaths. These animals were supposed to be brought to shelters, but were later found injured or dead below this 50-ft-high bridge in [[Vega Baja]]. After instituting a no-pet policy for three housing projects, the city supposedly hired the Animal Control Solutions company to retrieve pets from families that did not follow the policy and bring them to shelters to be adopted or [[euthanize]]d humanely. Some 80 dogs and cats were dead and another 80 badly injured. Upon investigation, some of the pets were thought to have already been dead, but many were not.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=http://news.nationalgeographic.com/news/2007/11/071115-AP-pet-murders_2.html|title=Pets Massacred in Puerto Rico|last=Danica Coto|first=Kaila Diaz|date=2007|website=National Geographic|publisher=The Associated Press|access-date=October 27, 2016}}</ref>\n\nWhen the owner of the Animal Control company learned of this accusation, he denied it. He claimed that these animals could not be proved to be the same dogs that his men had retrieved from the housing projects.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== Further reading ==\n* Robin, Finn. \"The Saviour of Dead Dog Beach Boxing Champ Rescues Puerto Rico's unwanted dogs.\" ''Hamilton Spectator'', The (ON) n.d.: Newspaper Source Plus. Web. October 18, 2016.\n*  Heather Long. [http://www.reviewjournal.com/news/nation-and-world/puerto-rico-amid-economic-crisis-has-become-dead-dog-island \"Puerto Rico, amid Economic Crisis, Has Become 'Dead Dog Island'\"] ''Las Vegas Review Journal'' (2016): n. pag. ''Las Vegas Review-Journal''. March 21, 2016. Web. October 27, 2016.\n\n[[Category:Beaches of Puerto Rico]]\n[[Category:Yabucoa, Puerto Rico]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Beach in Yabucoa, Puerto Rico}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=December 2019}}\n\n'''Dead Dog Beach''', also known as '''Sato Beach''' and officially named '''Playa Lucia''', is a beach within the municipality of [[Yabucoa]] in southeastern [[Puerto Rico]]. Its \"Dead Dog Beach\" came because it is the dumping ground for stray animals, mainly dogs that the inhabitants of Yabucoa can no longer afford. Most are not [[spayed]] or [[neutered]]; in [[Puerto Rican culture]], cutting a dog's \"manhood\" is seen as inappropriate/cruel. The strays [[breed]] uncontrollably, giving rise to more homeless dogs.\n\nDead Dog Beach was known for one of the highest concentrations of stray animals in the country. It attracted [[animal rights activist]]s and groups hoping to make a difference. One example is The Sato Project, a large-scale [[rescue]] project focusing its efforts on Sato Beach/Yabucoa.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thesatoproject.org/|title=The Sato Project|website=The Sato Project|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-26}}</ref> Many individuals who come are so moved by these animals' living conditions that they extend their stay and help. Various rescue projects focus on the island's development. Many of these efforts were prompted by abuse of animals, even by local authorities, as in the Barceloneta Massacre in 2007.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cbsnews.com/news/more-than-50-pets-massacred-in-puerto-rico/|title=More Than 50 Pets Massacred In Puerto Rico|website=www.cbsnews.com|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-26}}</ref>\n\n== Geography and climate ==\n[[Puerto Rico]], mainly a 90-by-30 mile island located in the [[Caribbean]] region, includes smaller islands off of its eastern coast. Its average temperatures range from 70-80 degrees [[Fahrenheit]]. Its beaches stretch for hundreds of miles.<ref>Barreto, Maritza (2017). Assessment of beach morphology at Puerto Rico Island. Puerto Rico and Caribbean Beach Network. retrieved from: http://drna.pr.gov/wp-content/uploads/2017/05/Geomorphic-Assessment-of-Puerto-Rico-1977-to-2016.pdf</ref> Along the northern coasts, are cliffs and a region known as the [[Karst]] region. This region contains notable land features such as caves, caverns, waterfalls, underground rivers and rain forests. Puerto Rico has the largest and deepest trench in the [[Atlantic Ocean]], known as the [[Puerto Rico Trench]].<ref name=Landforms>{{Cite web|url=http://www.worldatlas.com/webimage/countrys/namerica/caribb/puertorico/prland.htm|title=Geography of Puerto Rico, Landforms - World Atlas|website=www.worldatlas.com|access-date=2016-11-14}}</ref> Notable rivers include the [[Guayan\u00e9s River (Yabucoa, Puerto Rico)|Guayanes River]] extends for 17 miles, as well as the [[Prieto River (Ponce, Puerto Rico)|Prieto]], [[Arenas River (Yabucoa, Puerto Rico)|Arenas]], [[Limones River|Limones]] and [[Ingenio River|Ingenio Rivers]].<ref name=enciclopediapr>{{Cite web|url=http://www.enciclopediapr.org/ing/article.cfm?ref=09052002|title=Municipalities: Yabucoa|website=www.enciclopediapr.org|access-date=2016-11-07}}</ref>\n\nYabucoa is surrounded on three sides by the San Lorenzo Batholith and the Caribbean Sea. It is [[humid]] and mainly flat. Mountain ranges in this area include Santa Elena peak, Pandura, and the Cayey Range.  Yabucoa valley consists mainly of farmland. It was originally a small mountain town.<ref name=enciclopediapr/>\n\n== History ==\nThe name [[Yabucoa, Puerto Rico|Yubucoa]] means \"place or site with waters\", although some scholars believe it means \"place of cassava\".<ref name=enciclopediapr/> The area was founded in 1793 when Manuel Col\u00f3n de Bonillas and his wife, Catalina Morales Pacheco, donated the settlement.<ref name=enciclopediapr/> [[Puerto Rico]] was a [[Spanish colony]] until 1898, when it became a U.S. territory.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cia.gov/library/publications/the-world-factbook/geos/rq.html|title=Central America :: Puerto Rico \u2014 The World Factbook - Central Intelligence Agency|website=www.cia.gov|access-date=2020-03-25}}</ref> Economic hardship dates back to the 17th and 18th centuries. Although briefly resolved, such hardships play a key role in the story of Dead Dog Beach. Yabucoa received popularity when in 1989 the [[WBO]] held a boxing championship there between [[Orlando Fernandez]] and [[Julio Gervacio]]. Fernandez' victory brought attention to the town and to Puerto Rico.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.fightsrec.com/orlando-fernandez.html|title=Orlando Fernandez boxer|website=www.fightsrec.com|access-date=2016-11-07}}</ref>\n\nBefore becoming known as \"Dead Dog Beach,\" Playa Lucia was once a popular beach. It consisted of a pool, cabana facilities and other recreational activities. It became a wasteland: the pool was covered in graffiti, and full of garbage. The facilities were abandoned and without proper maintenance turned into ruins. The only visitors who roamed the area were dogs and cats among the piles of pet carcasses.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.cnn.com/2015/08/25/living/sato-project-dead-dog-beach-puerto-rico/index.html|title=Sato Project saves pups from 'Dead Dog Beach'|author=Ann Roche and Evelio Contreras|website=CNN|access-date=2016-11-14}}</ref> As of 2014, a gate was put up to deny access to people who would dump dogs on the beach and Sato Project has been regularly monitoring the beach for strays.<ref name=\"stitcher\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.stitcher.com/s?eid=41157978|title=Hope For The Lost And Abandoned Dogs Of Puerto Rico from The Animal House &#124; WAMU 88.5|website=www.stitcher.com}}</ref><ref name=\"thesatoproject\">{{cite web|url=https://www.thesatoproject.org/spayathon|title=The Spayathon for Puerto Rico|website=The Sato Project|accessdate=2020-03-14}}</ref>\n\n== Causes  ==\n\n=== Economy ===\nThe [[Economy of Puerto Rico#Finance|economy of Puerto Rico]] weakened under the weight of the 2017 [[Puerto Rico#Hurricanes Irma and Maria|hurricanes]]. Many individuals were forced to abandon their pets. Local [[Animal shelter|shelter]]s filled and individuals left the island.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://money.cnn.com/2016/03/20/news/economy/puerto-rico-crisis-stray-dogs/index.html|title=Puerto Rico has become 'dead dog island'|last=Long|first=Heather|date=2016-03-20|website=CNNMoney|access-date=2016-11-14}}</ref>\n\n=== Culture ===\nThe practice of not spaying and neutering pets causes population to expand rapidly. A majority of Puerto Rican pet owners believe that it sterilization is not \"natural\" and/or \"kills their sex life\". Other owners breed their animals as a source of income. Some individuals go so far as to argue that it is less humane to kill their pet's \"sex lives\" than to actually kill the pet.<ref>{{Citation|via=DrunkenGunsAndBombs on YouTube|title=100,000|first=Juan Agust\u00edn|last=M\u00e1rquez|date=2012-09-07|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=yWkXtxXq84M|accessdate=2016-11-14}}</ref>\n\n== Rescue projects ==\n\n=== SATO Project ===\nThe Sato Project is an animal rescue project that operates across the territory while mainly focusing on Dead Dog Beach. Launched in 2011 by Chrissy Beckles and her husband Bobby Beckles, it is the official rescue group in Yabucoa. The Sato Project is composed of two teams: one within Puerto Rico and another in the United States. These teams work together to ship the dogs to the U.S.\n\nThe process of helping these animals begins with logging and identifying them on the beach. Once logged, the Beach Coordinator checks on the animals and provides food and medicine until shelter space becomes available. Shelter dogs receive a full [[check-up]]: a [[veterinarian]] provides any necessary care. In addition to a check-up, the dogs are also spayed/neutered and [[vaccinate]]d. When the dog is well enough to travel, volunteers in Puerto Rico prepare it to fly to either [[JFK Airport|JFK]] or [[Newark Airport]]<nowiki/>s. Upon arrival the dogs are transported by another team of volunteers to the project's adoption team. The latter works to find every dog a home. They will take dogs back upon an owner's request.<ref name=\"What We Do\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.thesatoproject.org/what-we-do/|title=What We Do|website=The Sato Project|access-date=2016-11-14}}</ref>\n\n==== Spay and neuter campaign ====\nThe Sato Project began a multi-phase campaign to facilitate and promote free spaying and neutering events in the area. The first major phase started in 2015 when local government agreed to put up cameras and a gated fence on the beach. This fence is meant to keep people from releasing animals there or abusing the current animal population after hours.\n\nThe second phase was set to start in March 2016. It was to include three parts:\n\n* Team with the [[Humane Society International]] to hold ten spay, neuter, and [[microchipping]] clinics throughout Yabucoa\n* Target low income neighborhoods to provide pet owners with 30 free vouchers per month for access to free spaying, neutering, and microchipping at veterinary clinics in Yabucoa. \n* Fight the [[overpopulation]] and current conditions by involving the community with the goal of helping at least 30 dogs per month.<ref name=\"What We Do\" />\n\n=== Other rescue operations ===\nThe [[Animal Rescue Foundation]] is an animal rescue project started in 1997 which primarily operates in [[Rinc\u00f3n, Puerto Rico|Rincon]]. Its main focus is to rescue dogs and cats, provide spaying/neutering and adoption services, and to educate the community about pet safety.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://arfrincon.org/about-arf/|title=Animal Rescue Foundations|last=|first=|date=|website=|publisher=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\nBarks For Hope is a rescue foundation started by Leo Roubian in 2014. Its primary goal is to provide aid and adoption for abandoned animals throughout the island. The operation offers transportation and medical care, including rehabilitation and rides to be spayed and neutered.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.barksofhope.org/|title=Barks for Hope|last=|first=|date=|website=|publisher=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\n==== Individual rescue efforts ====\nStephen McGarva moved to Puerto Rico in 2005, and, while exploring his new home, came face-to-face with the animals' plight. McGarva began feeding the dogs and cleaning their [[wound]]s daily, in the hope that it would help make them more adoptable. McGarva remained in the territory for several years to take care of the animals before returning the U.S. where by sharing his experiences, raised awareness of the animal crisis in Puerto Rico.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://nypost.com/2014/08/24/hundreds-of-dogs-saved-from-massacre-on-puerto-rico/|title=Hundreds of dogs saved from massacre on Puerto Rico|last=Buiso|first=Gary|date=2014-08-24|website=New York Post|language=en|access-date=2020-03-25}}</ref>\n\n== Barceloneta massacre ==\nIn fall 2007, Puerto Rican animal control captured dozens of dogs and cats from housing projects around Barceloneta and allegedly threw them off a bridge to their deaths. These animals were supposed to be brought to shelters, but were later found injured or dead below this 50-ft-high bridge in [[Vega Baja]]. After instituting a no-pet policy for three housing projects, the city supposedly hired the Animal Control Solutions company to retrieve pets from families that did not follow the policy and bring them to shelters to be adopted or [[euthanize]]d humanely. Some 80 dogs and cats were dead and another 80 badly injured. Upon investigation, some of the pets were thought to have already been dead, but many were not.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=http://news.nationalgeographic.com/news/2007/11/071115-AP-pet-murders_2.html|title=Pets Massacred in Puerto Rico|last=Danica Coto|first=Kaila Diaz|date=2007|website=National Geographic|publisher=The Associated Press|access-date=October 27, 2016}}</ref>\n\nWhen the owner of the Animal Control company learned of this accusation, he denied it. He claimed that these animals could not be proved to be the same dogs that his men had retrieved from the housing projects.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== Further reading ==\n* Robin, Finn. \"The Saviour of Dead Dog Beach Boxing Champ Rescues Puerto Rico's unwanted dogs.\" ''Hamilton Spectator'', The (ON) n.d.: Newspaper Source Plus. Web. October 18, 2016.\n*  Heather Long. [http://www.reviewjournal.com/news/nation-and-world/puerto-rico-amid-economic-crisis-has-become-dead-dog-island \"Puerto Rico, amid Economic Crisis, Has Become 'Dead Dog Island'\"] ''Las Vegas Review Journal'' (2016): n. pag. ''Las Vegas Review-Journal''. March 21, 2016. Web. October 27, 2016.\n\n[[Category:Beaches of Puerto Rico]]\n[[Category:Yabucoa, Puerto Rico]]\n", "name_user": "The Eloquent Peasant", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eHistory:link", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dead_Dog_Beach"}
{"title_page": "Coggin College of Business", "text_new": "{{Infobox university\n|name           = Coggin College of Business\n|established    = 1972\n|type           = [[Public]] [[Business School]]\n|dean           = Mark C. Dawkins \n|city           = [[Jacksonville, Florida]] \n|country        = U.S.\n|students       = \u22482600 [[Undergraduate]]\n                  \u2248250 [[Postgraduate]]\n|faculty        = 101\n|campus         = \n|website= {{url|www.unf.edu/coggin}}\n}}\n\nThe '''Coggin College of Business''' is the business school at the [[University of North Florida]]. About 2,850 students are enrolled in the college, including [[undergraduate]] and [[graduate school|graduate]] students. Programs are offered in the fields of  Accounting, Economics, Finance, Financial Services, International Business, Management, Marketing and Transportation & Logistics. The Coggin College of Business is one of UNF's three original colleges.  Two of the college's programs, the international business program and the transportation and logistics program are designated as flagship programs at UNF.<ref>[http://www.redorbit.com/news/education/537319/2_unf_coggin_college_of_gbusiness_majors_designated_flagship/index.html ]{{dead link|date=January 2014}}</ref>  Coggin is [[accredited]] by the Commission on Colleges of the Southern Association of Colleges and Schools and the [[Association to Advance Collegiate Schools of Business|AACSB]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.unf.edu/coggin/about/facts.htm |accessdate=July 3, 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080720092101/http://www.unf.edu/coggin/about/facts.htm |archivedate=July 20, 2008 }}</ref>  [[The Princeton Review]] included Coggin College in the 2008 edition of \"Best 290 Business Schools\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.jacksonville.com/tu-online/stories/101007/bus_206727011.shtml |title=Business briefs: Coggin school gets business recognition |publisher=Jacksonville.com |date=2007-10-10 |accessdate=2014-01-18}}</ref> and again for the 2018 edition, marking over a decade on the list.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.unf.edu/coggin/about/ |title=About |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |website=unf.edu |publisher=unf|access-date=2 March 2016 |quote=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://news.wjct.org/post/business-brief-why-unfs-business-school-among-countrys-best |title=Why UNF's Business School is Among Country's Best|author=WJCT|website=wjct.org|publisher=WJCT|access-date=16 Feb 2017 |quote=}}</ref>\n\nSince 1973, the college's alumni totals over 13,500.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.unf.edu/coggin/about/facts.htm |accessdate=July 3, 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080720092101/http://www.unf.edu/coggin/about/facts.htm |archivedate=July 20, 2008 }}</ref>\n\nThe college was named the Coggin College of Business in 2002 honoring Luther and Blanch Coggin, after a $5 million gift.\n==Academics==\nThe college offers both undergraduate and graduate degrees in multiple areas of study. [[File:Coggin College and lake UNF.JPG|right|thumb| View of the college from the Student Union Boathouse.]] Undergraduates pursue the Bachelor of Business Administration degree, for which various major and minor fields of study are offered.\n\nGraduates have available three different degree programs. The [[Master of Accountancy]] program is designed to prepare students for public accounting careers, providing enough credit hours to sit for state CPA exams. The [[Master of Science in Management]] program is a generalist business degree with a focus on management.  The [[Master of Business Administration]] program is designed to prepare students to take on advanced leadership roles in business organizations by synthesizing various business disciplines into management strategy. \n\nThe MBA program curriculum is structured around three groupings of core subject classes including marketing, management, finance, accounting, and economics.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.unf.edu/catalog/link/CCB-MBABBUS/ |title=Curicculum |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |website=unf.edu |publisher=unf |access-date=4 March 2016 |quote=}}</ref>  In addition three elective courses are taken.  Students have the option to use these electives to concentrate in an area of study, such as further study in core subjects or other areas for example, international business, but are not required to.  All core courses are offered in the fall, spring, and summer; electives are generally offered only in the spring and fall.  The MBA program maintains a balance in instruction methods utilizing lecture, [[Case method|case studies]], and group based projects such as simulations.  \n\nIn addition to these programs Coggin offers a graduate certificate in e-Business.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.unf.edu/coggin/academics/graduate/certificates.aspx |title=Certificates |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |website=unf.edu |publisher=unf |access-date=4 March 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160307062002/https://www.unf.edu/coggin/academics/graduate/certificates.aspx |archive-date=7 March 2016 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n==Student Organizations==\nThe Osprey Financial Group is the college's student managed investment fund. The group is a combination class/student organization; over the course of two semesters selected students are given the opportunity to manage a real portfolio of investments.  Students gain real world money management experience as well as experience in using investment tools such as [[Bloomberg terminal|Bloomberg Terminals]] and [[Morningstar, Inc.|Morningstar's]] investment analysis platform.  The group is housed in the State Farm Companies Foundation Center for Financial Research in the Coggin Business Administration Building.\n\nAdditionally, Coggin is also  host to many subject specific clubs and organizations, including:\n*[[Alpha Kappa Psi]]\n*Alpha Sigma Pi\n*[[American Marketing Association]]\n*[[Delta Sigma Pi]]\n*[[Rotaract]]\n*[[Beta Gamma Sigma]] Business Honor Society.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.unf.edu/coggin/about/business_centers/index.aspx |title=Organizations |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |website= |publisher= |access-date=4 March 2016 |quote=}}</ref>\n==Study Abroad and International Partners==\nThe Coggin College of Business offers numerous opportunities for students to study abroad.  One option is short term faculty lead trips usually around 10 days in length. Another is semester long exchanges in countries such as UAE, UK, China, Argentina, and Germany among others.  Dual degree programs are also available.  Undergraduates can earn dual degrees with UNF and [[KEDGE Business School]] in France.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.unf.edu/coggin/academics/undergrad.aspx |title=Undergrad |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |website=unf.edu |publisher=unf |access-date=2 March 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151128123253/http://www.unf.edu/coggin/academics/undergrad.aspx |archive-date=28 November 2015 |url-status=dead }}</ref>  Graduate students have available the GlobalMBA program.  In this program students spend one semester each at four universities: The [[Technical University of Cologne]] in Germany, [[Dongbei University of Finance and Economics]] in China, the [[University of Warsaw]] in Poland, and [[University of North Florida|UNF]].  Upon completion students earn an MBA from UNF and a Master of International Management and Intercultural Communication jointly from the University of Warsaw and the Technical University of Cologne.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.unf.edu/coggin/international/globalmba/GlobalMBA.aspx |title=GlobalMBA |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |website=unf.edu |publisher=unf |access-date=2 March 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160314074723/http://www.unf.edu/coggin/international/globalmba/GlobalMBA.aspx |archive-date=14 March 2016 |url-status=dead }}</ref>  \n\n==Business Centers==\nCoggin business centers focus on research in different subjects to provide a diverse range of business data to the Jacksonville community.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.unf.edu/coggin/about/business_centers/index.aspx |title=Business Centers |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |website=unf.edu |publisher=unf |access-date=4 March 2016 |quote=}}</ref>  \n* Coggin Center for Entrepreneurship and Innovation, located in downtown Jacksonville.\n* Center for International Business Studies, part of the flagship international business program.\n* Local Economic Indicators Project, economic research focusing on Jacksonville and the state of Florida as well as US and world trends.\n* Small Business Development Center, part of the Florida SBDC network and the National Association of Small Business Development Centers.\n \n==Facility==\n[[File:Coggin College of Business.jpg|right|thumb|]]\nThe Coggin College of Business Administration building (or building 42) is the home of the college. The {{convert|60000|sqft|m2|adj=on}} facility has fourteen classrooms (with capacities of 36-54),  an auditorium, three business technology classrooms, five student skills labs, and a special Trading Room for student Investment Analysts of the Osprey Financial Group.  The facility houses numerous administrative and professor's offices as well as the Career Management Center, offering internship and career services exclusively for Coggin students. The building opened in 1996 at a cost of $7.8 million.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.unf.edu/coggin/about/timeline.htm |title=Timeline |accessdate=July 3, 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080905123156/http://www.unf.edu/coggin/about/timeline.htm |archivedate=September 5, 2008 }}</ref>\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.unf.edu/coggin/ Official website]\n\n==References==\n<references/>\n\n{{coord missing|Jacksonville}}\n\n{{University of North Florida}}\n\n[[Category:Business schools in Florida]]\n[[Category:Educational institutions established in 1972]]\n[[Category:University of North Florida]]\n[[Category:University subdivisions in Florida]]\n[[Category:1972 establishments in Florida]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox university\n|name           = Coggin College of Business\n|established    = 1972\n|type           = [[Public]] [[Business School]]\n|dean           = Mark C. Dawkins \n|city           = [[Jacksonville, Florida]] \n|country        = U.S.\n|students       = \u22482600 [[Undergraduate]]\n                  \u2248250 [[Postgraduate]]\n|faculty        = 101\n|campus         = \n|website= {{url|www.unf.edu/coggin}}\n}}\n\nThe '''Coggin College of Business''' is the business school at the [[University of North Florida]]. About 2,850 students are enrolled in the college, including [[undergraduate]] and [[graduate school|graduate]] students. Programs are offered in the fields of  Accounting, Economics, Finance, Financial Services, International Business, Management, Marketing and Transportation & Logistics. The Coggin College of Business is one of UNF's three original colleges.  Two of the college's programs, the international business program and the transportation and logistics program are designated as flagship programs at UNF.<ref>[http://www.redorbit.com/news/education/537319/2_unf_coggin_college_of_gbusiness_majors_designated_flagship/index.html ]{{dead link|date=January 2014}}</ref>  Coggin is [[accredited]] by the Commission on Colleges of the Southern Association of Colleges and Schools and the [[Association to Advance Collegiate Schools of Business|AACSB]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.unf.edu/coggin/about/facts.htm |accessdate=July 3, 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080720092101/http://www.unf.edu/coggin/about/facts.htm |archivedate=July 20, 2008 }}</ref>  [[The Princeton Review]] included Coggin College in the 2008 edition of \"Best 290 Business Schools\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.jacksonville.com/tu-online/stories/101007/bus_206727011.shtml |title=Business briefs: Coggin school gets business recognition |publisher=Jacksonville.com |date=2007-10-10 |accessdate=2014-01-18}}</ref> and again for the 2018 edition, marking over a decade on the list.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.unf.edu/coggin/about/ |title=About |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |website=unf.edu |publisher=unf|access-date=2 March 2016 |quote=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://news.wjct.org/post/business-brief-why-unfs-business-school-among-countrys-best |title=Why UNF's Business School is Among Country's Best|author=WJCT|website=wjct.org|publisher=WJCT|access-date=16 Feb 2017 |quote=}}</ref>\n\nSince 1973, the college's alumni totals over 13,500.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.unf.edu/coggin/about/facts.htm |accessdate=July 3, 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080720092101/http://www.unf.edu/coggin/about/facts.htm |archivedate=July 20, 2008 }}</ref>\n\nThe college was named the Coggin College of Business in 2002 honoring Luther and Blanch Coggin, after a $5 million gift.\n==Academics==\nThe college offers both undergraduate and graduate degrees in multiple areas of study. [[File:Coggin College and lake UNF.JPG|right|thumb| View of the college from the Student Union Boathouse.]] Undergraduates pursue the Bachelor of Business Administration degree, for which various major and minor fields of study are offered.\n\nGraduates have available three different degree programs. The [[Master of Accountancy]] program is designed to prepare students for public accounting careers, providing enough credit hours to sit for state CPA exams. The [[Master of Science in Management]] program is a generalist business degree with a focus on management.  The [[Masters of Business Administration]] program is designed to prepare students to take on advanced leadership roles in business organizations by synthesizing various business disciplines into management strategy. \n\nThe MBA program curriculum is structured around three groupings of core subject classes including marketing, management, finance, accounting, and economics.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.unf.edu/catalog/link/CCB-MBABBUS/ |title=Curicculum |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |website=unf.edu |publisher=unf |access-date=4 March 2016 |quote=}}</ref>  In addition three elective courses are taken.  Students have the option to use these electives to concentrate in an area of study, such as further study in core subjects or other areas for example, international business, but are not required to.  All core courses are offered in the fall, spring, and summer; electives are generally offered only in the spring and fall.  The MBA program maintains a balance in instruction methods utilizing lecture, [[Case method|case studies]], and group based projects such as simulations.  \n\nIn addition to these programs Coggin offers a graduate certificate in e-Business.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.unf.edu/coggin/academics/graduate/certificates.aspx |title=Certificates |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |website=unf.edu |publisher=unf |access-date=4 March 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160307062002/https://www.unf.edu/coggin/academics/graduate/certificates.aspx |archive-date=7 March 2016 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n==Student Organizations==\nThe Osprey Financial Group is the college's student managed investment fund. The group is a combination class/student organization; over the course of two semesters selected students are given the opportunity to manage a real portfolio of investments.  Students gain real world money management experience as well as experience in using investment tools such as [[Bloomberg terminal|Bloomberg Terminals]] and [[Morningstar, Inc.|Morningstar's]] investment analysis platform.  The group is housed in the State Farm Companies Foundation Center for Financial Research in the Coggin Business Administration Building.\n\nAdditionally, Coggin is also  host to many subject specific clubs and organizations, including:\n*[[Alpha Kappa Psi]]\n*Alpha Sigma Pi\n*[[American Marketing Association]]\n*[[Delta Sigma Pi]]\n*[[Rotaract]]\n*[[Beta Gamma Sigma]] Business Honor Society.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.unf.edu/coggin/about/business_centers/index.aspx |title=Organizations |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |website= |publisher= |access-date=4 March 2016 |quote=}}</ref>\n==Study Abroad and International Partners==\nThe Coggin College of Business offers numerous opportunities for students to study abroad.  One option is short term faculty lead trips usually around 10 days in length. Another is semester long exchanges in countries such as UAE, UK, China, Argentina, and Germany among others.  Dual degree programs are also available.  Undergraduates can earn dual degrees with UNF and [[KEDGE Business School]] in France.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.unf.edu/coggin/academics/undergrad.aspx |title=Undergrad |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |website=unf.edu |publisher=unf |access-date=2 March 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151128123253/http://www.unf.edu/coggin/academics/undergrad.aspx |archive-date=28 November 2015 |url-status=dead }}</ref>  Graduate students have available the GlobalMBA program.  In this program students spend one semester each at four universities: The [[Technical University of Cologne]] in Germany, [[Dongbei University of Finance and Economics]] in China, the [[University of Warsaw]] in Poland, and [[University of North Florida|UNF]].  Upon completion students earn an MBA from UNF and a Master of International Management and Intercultural Communication jointly from the University of Warsaw and the Technical University of Cologne.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.unf.edu/coggin/international/globalmba/GlobalMBA.aspx |title=GlobalMBA |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |website=unf.edu |publisher=unf |access-date=2 March 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160314074723/http://www.unf.edu/coggin/international/globalmba/GlobalMBA.aspx |archive-date=14 March 2016 |url-status=dead }}</ref>  \n\n==Business Centers==\nCoggin business centers focus on research in different subjects to provide a diverse range of business data to the Jacksonville community.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.unf.edu/coggin/about/business_centers/index.aspx |title=Business Centers |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |website=unf.edu |publisher=unf |access-date=4 March 2016 |quote=}}</ref>  \n* Coggin Center for Entrepreneurship and Innovation, located in downtown Jacksonville.\n* Center for International Business Studies, part of the flagship international business program.\n* Local Economic Indicators Project, economic research focusing on Jacksonville and the state of Florida as well as US and world trends.\n* Small Business Development Center, part of the Florida SBDC network and the National Association of Small Business Development Centers.\n \n==Facility==\n[[File:Coggin College of Business.jpg|right|thumb|]]\nThe Coggin College of Business Administration building (or building 42) is the home of the college. The {{convert|60000|sqft|m2|adj=on}} facility has fourteen classrooms (with capacities of 36-54),  an auditorium, three business technology classrooms, five student skills labs, and a special Trading Room for student Investment Analysts of the Osprey Financial Group.  The facility houses numerous administrative and professor's offices as well as the Career Management Center, offering internship and career services exclusively for Coggin students. The building opened in 1996 at a cost of $7.8 million.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.unf.edu/coggin/about/timeline.htm |title=Timeline |accessdate=July 3, 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080905123156/http://www.unf.edu/coggin/about/timeline.htm |archivedate=September 5, 2008 }}</ref>\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.unf.edu/coggin/ Official website]\n\n==References==\n<references/>\n\n{{coord missing|Jacksonville}}\n\n{{University of North Florida}}\n\n[[Category:Business schools in Florida]]\n[[Category:Educational institutions established in 1972]]\n[[Category:University of North Florida]]\n[[Category:University subdivisions in Florida]]\n[[Category:1972 establishments in Florida]]\n", "name_user": "EdmundT", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eAcademics:Spelling", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Coggin_College_of_Business"}
{"title_page": "Todd Hido", "text_new": "{{Infobox artist\n| name          = Todd Hido\n| image         = Todd Hido by McCall - CC.jpg\n| caption       = Todd Hido, Montana, 2019\n| birth_name    =\n| birth_date    = {{Birth date and age|1968|08|25}}\n| birth_place   = [[Kent, Ohio]], United States\n| death_date    =\n| death_place   =\n| nationality   = [[United States|American]]\n| field         = [[Photography]]\n| education     = [[Bachelor of Fine Arts|B.F.A.]] \u2013 [[School of the Museum of Fine Arts, Boston]] <br/> [[Master of Fine Arts|M.F.A.]] \u2013 [[California College of the Arts]]\n| training      =\n| movement      =\n| works         =\n| patrons       =\n| influenced    =\n| awards        =\n| website       = {{URL|www.toddhido.com}}\n}}\n\n'''Todd Hido''' (born 25 August 1968)<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bu.edu/prc/prcpov/artists/a16.html|title=Todd Hido|website=Bu.edu|accessdate=14 December 2017}}</ref> is an American [[contemporary artist]] and photographer.<ref>{{cite web|accessdate=2018-12-03|title=Todd Hido|url=http://www.artnet.com/artists/todd-hido/|website=www.artnet.com}}</ref> He has produced 17 books,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/artanddesign/photography-blog/2013/oct/02/unseen-photo-fair-amsterdam-review|title=A window on weird: step inside the Unseen Photo fair in Amsterdam|first=Sean|last=O'Hagan|date=2 October 2013|accessdate=14 December 2017|website=Theguardian.com}}</ref> had his work exhibited widely and included in various public collections.<ref>https://www.mmoca.org/learn/teachers/teaching-pages/todd-hido</ref>\n\n== Life and work ==\nHido was born August 25, 1968, in [[Kent, Ohio]], and graduated from [[Theodore Roosevelt High School (Kent, Ohio)|Theodore Roosevelt High School]] in 1986.<ref>{{cite web |title= Kent City Schools Hall of Fame archives|url=https://www.kentschools.net/hall-of-fame/hall-of-fame-archives/ |year=2009 |work=KentSchools.net |publisher=Kent City School District |accessdate=January 20, 2020}}</ref> He graduated in 1991 with a B.F.A. from [[Tufts University]],<ref>{{cite news|accessdate=December 3, 2018 |title=Todd Hido: Sources and Influences \u2013 Aperture Foundation NY|url=https://aperture.org/workshops-classes/hido-2015/|newspaper=Aperture Foundation NY}}</ref> in [[Medford, Massachusetts]] and [[School of the Museum of Fine Arts, Boston]]. Between 1991 and 1992 he studied at [[Rhode Island School of Design]], [[Providence, Rhode Island]].<ref name=\"hido-bio\">{{cite web|url=http://www.toddhido.com/|title=Todd Hido|website=Toddhido.com|accessdate=December 14, 2017}}</ref> In 1996 he gained an M.F.A. from [[California College of Arts and Crafts]], [[Oakland, California]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cca.edu/academics/graduate/alumni|title=Graduate Alumni \u2013 California College of the Arts|website=Cca.edu|accessdate=December 14, 2017}}</ref>\n\nCurrently based in [[San Francisco]], much of Hido's earlier work involves photographs of urban and suburban housing<ref>{{cite web|url=http://designobserver.com/feature/exposure-suburban-house-at-night-by-todd-hido/39120/|title=Exposure: Surburban house at night, photographed by Todd Hido.|website=Designobserver.com |accessdate=December 14, 2017}}</ref> across the U.S.. He then started to include figures, mostly [[female nude]]s in interiors, and also to depict rural [[landscape]]s. In 2018, he released ''Bright Black World'', his first work photographed outside the U.S. with environmental overtones.\n\nHido says he is influenced by [[Alfred Hitchcock]], [[Edward Hopper]], [[Stephen Shore]], [[Robert Adams (photographer)|Robert Adams]], [[Walker Evans]], [[Nan Goldin]], [[Emmet Gowin]], [[Larry Sultan]], [[Alfred Stieglitz]], [[Andreas Gursky]] and [[Rineke Dijkstra]]. Commissioned by Italian brand [[Bottega Veneta]], he photographed actress [[Lauren Hutton]] as well as models [[Joan Smalls]] and [[Vittoria Ceretti]] for the brand's spring/summer 2017 advertisements.<ref>Alexandra Venison (January 16, 2017), [http://www.harpersbazaararabia.com/fashion/the-news/lauren-hutton-stars-in-the-bottega-veneta-springsummer2017-campaign Lauren Hutton Stars In The Bottega Veneta Spring/Summer 2017 Campaign] ''Harper's Bazaar Arabia''.</ref>\n\n== Publications ==\n=== Publications by Hido ===\n* ''House Hunting''.\n** Portland, OR: [[Nazraeli Press]], 2001. {{ISBN|978-3923922963}}.\n** Portland, OR: Nazraeli, 2007. {{ISBN|978-1590051931}}.\n* ''Outskirts''. Portland, OR: Nazraeli, 2002. {{ISBN|978-1590050286}}. Text by [[Luc Sante]]. Edition of 2000 copies.\n* ''Taft Street''. One Picture Book 6. Portland, OR: Nazraeli, 2001. {{ISBN|978-1590050170}}.\n* ''Roaming''. Portland, OR: Nazraeli, 2004. {{ISBN|978-1590050958}} Edition of 3000 copies.\n* ''Between the Two''. Portland, OR: Nazraeli, 2006. {{ISBN|978-1590051764}}. Edition of 2000 copies.\n* ''Crooked Cracked Tree in Fog''. One Picture Book 60. Portland, OR: Nazraeli, 2009. {{ISBN|978-1-59005-292-1}}. Edition of 500 copies.\n* ''Ohio.'' TBW Subscription Series #2. Oakland, CA: TBW, 2009. {{ASIN|B0087G1LD4}}. Edition of 800 copies. The other volumes are by Abner Nolan, Marianne Mueller and [[Alec Soth]].\n* ''A Road Divided''. Portland, OR: Nazraeli, 2010. {{ISBN|978-1590052662}}.\n* ''Nymph Daughters''. Kamakura: Super Labo, 2010. {{ISBN|9784905052012}}. Edition of 500 copies.\n* ''Excerpts from Silver Meadows''. Portland, OR: Nazraeli, 2013. {{ISBN|978-1590053683}}\n* ''Todd Hido on Landscapes, Interiors, and the Nude.'' The Photography Workshop Series. New York: [[Aperture Foundation|Aperture]], 2014. {{ISBN|978-1-59711-297-0}}. With an introduction by [[Gregory Halpern]].\n* ''B-Sides \u2013 Silver Meadows.'' Portland, OR: Nazraeli, 2014. {{ASIN|B00KP206DO}}. Edition of 500 copies. 50 individual cards in a clear plexi box, similar to a pack of playing cards.\n* ''Khrystyna's World.'' Amsterdam: Reflex Amsterdam, 2015. {{ISBN|978-90-71848-22-3}}. Edition of 500 copies. Published on the occasion of the exhibition, ''Todd Hido: Selections from a Survey: Khrystyna\u2019s World,'' September\u2013November 2015, Reflex Amsterdam, Amsterdam. With an essay by Katya Tylevich, \"Khrystyna's World: Detention in the Getaway Car\".<ref group=\"n\">A PDF of the book can be viewed [http://reflexamsterdam.com/wp-content/themes/newfish/pdf/todd-hido-khrystinas-world.pdf here within the Reflex Gallery website].</ref>\n* ''Seasons Road''. One Picture Book 93. Portland, OR: Nazraeli, 2016. {{ISBN|978-1-59005-456-7}}. Edition of 500 copies. 7 colour plates and 1 photographic print. \"Every year at Christmas for the past ten years, Todd Hido has traveled to Ohio to visit his parents. During his annual trip home, Hido makes photographs along the small road that serves as the namesake for this book.\"<ref>[http://www.nazraeli.com/opb/todd-hido-one-picture-book-93-seasons-road \"Todd Hido | One Picture Book #93 : Seasons Road\"] Nazraeli Press. Accessed 5 October 2016</ref>\n* ''Intimate Distance: Twenty-five Years of Photographs, A Chronological Album.'' New York: Aperture, 2016. {{ISBN|978-1-59711-360-1}}. With an essay by [[David Campany]].\n* ''B-Sides Box Sets \u2013 Homing In.'' Oakland, CA: B-Sides Box Sets, 2017. {{ISBN|978-1-5323-5128-0}}. Edition of 2000 copies. 50 individual cards in a box. Previously unpublished photographs from ''House Hunting.''\n* ''Bright Black World.'' Paso Robles, CA: Nazraeli Press, 2018. {{ISBN|978-1590054758}}. Text by Alexander Nemerov.\n\n=== Smaller publications by Hido ===\n* ''Collage Number Three.'' Deadbeat Club #41. Los Angeles, CA: Deadbeat Club, 2016.  Edition of 500 copies. 8 page zine which folds out to form a poster.\n* ''The Perfect Copy Vol. 1.'' San Francisco, CA: Colpa Press, 2016. Six 4-color [[Risograph]] photographic prints in screen printed envelope. Edition of 100 copies.\n\n=== Publications edited or with contributions by Hido ===\n* ''Witness No. 7''. Portland, OR: Nazraeli, 2009. {{ISBN|978-1590052440}}. Photographs by Hido and [[Leon Borensztein]], and photographs of images from books by various people that have inspired Hido.\n* ''Cracked Trees''. One Picture Book 59. Portland, OR: Nazraeli, 2009. {{ISBN|978-1590052914}}. Photographs by Hido, paintings by 3rd grade students. Edition of 500 copies.\n* ''Motel Club.'' Nazraeli Press Six by Six, set 1 v. 4. Portland, OR: Nazraeli, 2010. {{ISBN|1590052978}}. Edition of 100 copies. The other volumes are by [[Anthony Hernandez (photographer)|Anthony Hernandez]], [[Raymond Meeks]], [[Martin Parr]], [[Toshio Shibata]] and [[Mark Steinmetz]].\n* ''Alec Soth's Lonely Boy Mag 2: Boys and Their Cars.'' St. Paul, MN: [[Alec Soth|Little Brown Mushroom]], 2011. Edition of 1000 copies. Text and photographs by Todd Hido, [[Alec Soth]], Chad States and erotic [[diorama]]s by Peter Davidson.\n* ''One Day \u2013 10 Photographers.'' Heidelberg: [[Kehrer Verlag|Kehrer]], 2010. {{ISBN|978-3-86828-173-6}}. A boxed set of ten books of photographs taken on 21 June 2010. Edited by [[Harvey Benge]], each book by one photographer including Todd Hido, Jessica Backhaus, [[Gerry Badger]], Harvey Benge, [[John Gossage]], [[Alec Soth]], [[Rob Hornstra]], [[Rinko Kawauchi]], Eva Maria Ocherbauer and Martin Parr.<ref group=\"n\">The publisher's description of this set: {{Cite web|url=https://www.kehrerverlag.com/en/one-day-10-photographers-978-3-86828-173-6|title=One Day \u2013 Kehrer Verlag|website=Kehrer Verlag|language=en|access-date=2018-04-05}}</ref>\n* ''Here.'', San Francisco: Pier 24 Photography, 2011. {{ISBN|978-0-9839917-0-0}}. Exhibition guide.\n* ''Leon Borensztein: American Portraits 1979\u20131989.'' Portland, OR: Nazraeli, 2011. {{ISBN|978-1-59005-305-8}}. Photographs by Leon Borensztein. Edited by Hido.\n* ''About Face'', San Francisco: Pier 24 Photography, 2012. {{ISBN|978-0-9839917-1-7}}. Exhibition guide\n* ''A Sense of Place'', San Francisco: Pier 24 Photography, 2013. {{ISBN|978-0-9839917-3-1}}. Exhibition guide.\n* ''About Face.'' San Francisco: Pier 24 Photography, 2014. {{ISBN|978-0-9839917-2-4}}. Exhibition catalog. Edition of 1000 copies. With forewords by Christopher McCall, and [[Richard Avedon]] (from ''In the American West''), an introduction by [[Philip Gefter]], and texts by [[Sandra S. Phillips]], and Ulrike Schneider.\n* ''The Open Road: Photography & the American Road Trip''. Edited and with text by [[David Campany]], photographs by Hido, [[Robert Frank]], [[Ed Ruscha]], [[Inge Morath]], [[Garry Winogrand]], [[William Egglestone]], [[Lee Friedlander]], [[Joel Meyerowitz]], [[Jacob Holdt]], [[Stephen Shore]], [[Bernard Plossu]], [[Victor Burgin]], [[Joel Sternfeld]], [[Shin'ya Fujiwara]], [[Alec Soth]], [[Ryan McGinley]], [[Justine Kurland]], and Taiyo Onorato and Nico Krebs.\n** New York: [[Aperture Foundation|Aperture]], 2014. {{ISBN|978-1-59711-240-6}}.\n** ''Road Trips: Voyages photographiques \u00e0 travers l\u2019Am\u00e9rique.'' Paris: Textuel, 2014. {{ISBN|9782845975002}}. French-language version.\n** ''En la Carretera: Viajes fotogr\u00e1ficos a trav\u00e9s de Norteam\u00e9rica.'' Madrid: La F\u00e1brica, 2014. {{ISBN|9788415691822}}. Spanish-language version.\n* ''A Sense of Place'', San Francisco: Pier 24 Photography, 2015. {{ISBN|978-0-9839917-4-8}}. Exhibition catalog. Edition of 1000 copies.\n\n== Exhibitions ==\n=== Solo ===\n{{BLP sources section|date=December 2018}}\n* 1997: SF Camerawork, San Francisco, CA.\n* 1998: ''House Hunting'', Stephen Wirtz Gallery, San Francisco, CA.\n* 1999: Inman Gallery, Houston TX.\n* 2000: ''Photographs Taken at Night,'' Kohn Turner Gallery, Los Angeles, CA. Julie Saul Gallery, New York, NY.\n* 2000: ''Homing In,'' Stephen Wirtz Gallery, San Francisco, CA.\n* 2001: ''New Photographs,'' Stephen Wirtz Gallery, San Francisco, CA. Inman Gallery, Houston, TX.\n* 2002: The Cleveland Museum of Art, Cleveland, Ohio.\n* 2002: ''Open House,'' Kemper Museum of Contemporary Art.\n* 2002: ''Roaming'', Paul Morris Gallery, New York, NY. Carrie Secrist Gallery, Chicago, IL. Taft Street, 3A Garage, San Francisco, CA.\n* 2003: Baldwin Gallery, Aspen Colorado. Carrie Secrist Gallery, Chicago, IL.\n* 2004: ''Roaming-New Landscapes'', Julie Saul Gallery, New York, NY.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://query.nytimes.com/gst/fullpage.html?res=9C01EEDB153BF93BA35753C1A9629C8B63 |author=Glueck, Grace|title=Art in Review : Todd Hido \u2013 'Roaming: New Landscapes'|newspaper=[[The New York Times]]|accessdate=October 8, 2004}}</ref>\n* 2004: ''Roaming'', Stephen Wirtz Gallery, San Francisco, CA. Carrie Secrist Gallery, Chicago, IL. Michael Berger Gallery, Pittsburgh, Pennsylvania. Baldwin Gallery, Aspen, Colorado.\n* 2005 Todd Hido, Sheppard Gallery, University of Nevada, Reno, NV. Inman Gallery, Houston, TX. Karyn Lovegrove Gallery, Los Angeles, CA.\n* 2006: ''Unfinished Narratives'', Photographic Center Northwest, Seattle, WA.\n* 2007: ''Between the Two'', Stephen Wirtz Gallery, San Francisco, CA.\n* 2007: Todd Hido, Rose Gallery, Santa Monica, CA.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.space15twenty.com/todd_hidos_a_road_divided |title=Space 15 Twenty |publisher=Space 15 Twenty |date= |accessdate=2014-04-19}}</ref>\n* 2008: ''A Road Divided''; Stephen Wirtz Gallery, San Francisco, CA.\n* 2008: ''Between the Two'', Yours Gallery, Warsaw, Poland.\n* 2009: ''A Road Divided''; [[Bruce Silverstein Gallery]], New York.\n* 2010: ''Househunting'' / ''Nudes''; Kaune, Sudendorf Gallery, Cologne, Germany.\n* 2011: ''A Road Divided''; Kaune, Posnik, Spohr Gallery, Cologne, Germany.\n* 2011: ''Fragmented Narratives''; Bruce Silverstein Gallery, New York.\n* 2012:  ''I Drive...'', La Galerie Particuli\u00e8re, Paris.\n* 2013:  ''Excerpts from Silver Meadows''; Kaune, Posnik, Spohr Gallery, Cologne, Germany.\n* 2015: ''Todd Hido: Selections from a Survey''; Casemore/Kirkeby, San Francisco, California<ref name=\"cmke\">https://casemorekirkeby.com/exhibitions/</ref>\n* 2016: ''Intimate Distance''; Casemore Kirkeby, San Francisco, California<ref name=\"cmke\" />\n* 2019: ''Bright Black World''; Casemore Kirkeby, San Francisco, California<ref name=\"cmke\" />\n\n=== Group ===\n* 2004: ''Light and Atmosphere,'' [[P\u00e9rez Art Museum Miami|Miami Art Museum]], FL, April 2004 \u2013 January 2005.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.pamm.org/exhibitions/light-and-atmosphere | access-date = 16 June 2016 | publisher = [[P\u00e9rez Art Museum Miami]] | title = Light and Atmosphere}}</ref>\n* 2006\u20132007: ''Suburban Escape,'' [[San Jose Museum of Art]], San Jose, CA, September 2006 \u2013 March 2007. Work  by Hido and 29 other photographers.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://sjmusart.org/exhibition/suburban-escape-art-california-sprawl | access-date = 16 June 2016 | publisher = [[San Jose Museum of Art]] | title = Suburban Escape: The Art of California Sprawl}}</ref>\n* 2010: ''Pier 24: The Inaugural Exhibition'', [[Pier 24 Photography]], San Francisco, CA, March\u2013June 2010.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://pier24.org/exhibition/pier-24-the-inaugural-exhibition/|title=Pier 24: The Inaugural Exhibition \u2013 Pier 24|website=Pier24.org|accessdate=14 December 2017}}</ref>\n* 2010: ''Day & Night,'' Main Exhibition Copenhagen Photo Festival, Copenhagen, Denmark.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://copenhagenphotofestival.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/02/CPF-PRESS.pdf |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2016-06-13 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150915092646/http://copenhagenphotofestival.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/02/CPF-PRESS.pdf |archivedate=2015-09-15 }}</ref>\n* 2011\u20132012: ''Here''., [[Pier 24 Photography]], San Francisco, CA, May 2011 \u2013 January 2012.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://pier24.org/exhibition/here/|title=Here. - Pier 24|website=Pier24.org|accessdate=14 December 2017}}</ref>\n* 2012\u20132013: ''About Face'', [[Pier 24 Photography]], San Francisco, CA, May 2012 \u2013 April 2013.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://pier24.org/exhibition/about-face/|title=About Face \u2013 Pier 24|website=Pier24.org|accessdate=14 December 2017}}</ref>\n* 2013\u20132014: ''A Sense of Place'', [[Pier 24 Photography]], San Francisco, CA, July 2013 \u2013 May 2014.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://pier24.org/exhibition/a-sense-of-place/|title=A Sense of Place \u2013 Pier 24|website=Pier24.org|accessdate=14 December 2017}}</ref>\n* 2016: ''The Open Road: Photography and the American Road Trip,'' [[Crystal Bridges Museum of American Art]], Bentonville, AR, February\u2013May 2016.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://crystalbridges.org/the-open-road/|title=The Open Road \u2013 Crystal Bridges Museum of American Art|website=crystalbridges.org|accessdate=14 December 2017}}</ref> Curated by [[David Campany]] and Denise Wolff.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://aperture.org/traveling-exhibitions/open-road/ | access-date = 11 March 2016 | publisher = [[Aperture Foundation]] | title = The Open Road: Photography and the American Road Trip: Curated by David Campany and Denise Wolff}}</ref>\n* 2016\u20132017: ''Collected'', Pier 24 Photography, San Francisco, CA, May 2016 \u2013 January 2017.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://pier24.org/exhibitions/|title=Exhibitions \u2013 Pier 24|website=Pier24.org|accessdate=14 December 2017}}</ref>\n\n== Awards ==\n* 1996: Barclay Simpson Award, [[California College of the Arts]], CA. Joinet winner with [[Geoffrey Chadsey]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://issuu.com/californiacollegeofthearts/docs/barclay25_catalog_lowres|title=Celebrating 25 Years of the Barclay Simpson Award|website=Issuu.com|accessdate=14 December 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cca.edu/calendar/2012/barclay-simpson-award-retrospective-exhibition-1987-2012|title=We're All Here Because We're Not All There \u2013 California College of the Arts|website=Cca.edu|accessdate=14 December 2017}}</ref>\n* 1998: The Wallace Alexander Gerbode Foundation, Visual Arts Award.<ref group=\"n\">The Wallace Alexander Gerbode Foundation's \"Special Awards Recipients 1987-Present\" PDF [http://foundationcenter.org/grantmaker/gerbode/docs/1987-Present-Recipients.pdf here] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150908025301/http://www.foundationcenter.org/grantmaker/gerbode/docs/1987-Present-Recipients.pdf |date=2015-09-08 }} does not list Hido.</ref>\n* 1998: Recent Graduate of Distinction Award, California College of the Arts, CA.{{citation needed|date=October 2015}}\n* 2001: Eureka Fellowship, Fleishhacker Foundation.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.fleishhackerfoundation.org/grants/eureka-fellowship-program/1999-2001/|title=The Fleishhacker Foundation \u2013 1999\u20132001|website=Fleishhackerfoundation.org|accessdate=14 December 2017}}</ref>\n* 2002: Best First Monograph of 2001, Photo-Eye.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.photoeye.com/bookstore/citation.cfm?catalog=PK802&i=3902289015&i2=|title=photo-eye Bookstore \u2013 Architecture of Time by Hiroshi Sugimoto \u2013 photobook|website=Photoeye.com|accessdate=14 December 2017}}</ref>\n* 2017: In Focus Artist selected by the National Portrait Gallery UK curators, an annual showcase for new work by an internationally renowned photographer <ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.npg.org.uk/whatson/event-root/november/in-conversation-13112017|title=In Conversation: Todd Hido \u2013 National Portrait Gallery|website=Npg.org.uk|accessdate=14 December 2017}}</ref>\n\n== Collections ==\nHido's work is held in the following public collections:\n{{col-list|colwidth=30em|\n* [[Art Institute of Chicago]], IL.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.artic.edu/aic/collections/artwork/artist/Hido,+Todd|title=Hido, Todd \u2013 The Art Institute of Chicago|website=Artic.edu|accessdate=14 December 2017}}</ref>\n* [[Amon Carter Museum of American Art]], Fort Worth, TX.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cartermuseum.org/artworks/779|title=Untitled #2431 \u2013 Todd Hido (b. 1968)|date=6 June 2008|website=Cartermuseum.org|accessdate=14 December 2017}}</ref>\n* [[Berkeley Art Museum and Pacific Film Archive]], Berkeley, CA.<ref>{{cite web|accessdate=2018-04-05|title=This Just In: Recent Acquisitions: BAMPFA|url=https://bampfa.org/program/just-recent-acquisitions|website=bampfa.org}}</ref>\n* [[Cleveland Museum of Art]], Cleveland, OH.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.clevelandart.org/art/2003.9|title=Untitled #2421 \u2013 Cleveland Museum of Art|website=Clevelandart.org|accessdate=14 December 2017}}</ref>\n* [[Di rosa]], Napa, CA.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dirosaart.org/wp-content/uploads/2011/07/Know-the-Rules-_PR.pdf|format=PDF|title=Know the Rules \u2013 Then Break Them Photography from the di Rosa Collection|website=Dirosaart.org\\accessdate=14 December 2017}}</ref>\n* [[George Eastman House]], Rochester, NY: 6 prints.<ref>https://collections.eastman.org/people/31393/todd-hido/objects</ref>\n* [[Kemper Museum of Contemporary Art]], Kansas City, MO.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.kemperart.org/exhibits/CatalogEssays/hidotodd.asp|title=Kemper Museum of Art Exhibitions|publisher=Kemperart.org|accessdate=30 September 2014}}</ref>\n* [[Los Angeles County Museum of Art]], CA.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://collections.lacma.org/node/159411|title=Todd Hido \u2013 LACMA Collections|website=collections.lacma.org|accessdate=14 December 2017}}</ref>\n* [[Madison Museum of Contemporary Art]], Madison, WI.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.mmoca.org/mmocacollects/artist_page.php?id=13 |title=The MMoCA Collects Site Has Moved |publisher=MMoCA |accessdate=2014-04-19 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140419212451/http://www.mmoca.org/mmocacollects/artist_page.php?id=13 |archivedate=2014-04-19 }}</ref>\n* [[Museum of Contemporary Photography]], Chicago, IL.<ref>{{cite web|accessdate=2018-04-05|title=Museum of Contemporary Photography|url=http://www.mocp.org/detail.php?t=objects&type=browse&f=maker&s=Hido%252C+Todd&record=0|website=www.mocp.org}}</ref>\n* [[Museum of Fine Arts, Boston]], MA.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mfa.org/collections/object/3235-479742|title=3235|date=3 April 2017|website=Mfa.org|accessdate=14 December 2017}}</ref>\n* [[Museum of Fine Arts, Houston]], TX.<ref>{{cite web|accessdate=2018-04-05|title=Untitled #2312-a |url=https://www.mfah.org/art/detail/76295?returnUrl=%252Fart%252Fsearch%253Fartist%253DTodd%252BHido%2526nationality%253DAmerican|website=www.mfah.org}}</ref>\n* [[National Science and Media Museum]], Bradford, UK: 2 prints<ref>https://collection.sciencemuseum.org.uk/people/cp134355/todd-hido</ref>\n* [[New York Public Library]], NY.<ref name=\"nypl\">\"[https://www.nypl.org/sites/default/files/Photographers_in_The_New_York_Public_Library_April_16_2010.pdf Photographers in The New York Public Library's Photography Collection]\". [[New York Public Library]]. Accessed 5 April 2018.</ref>\n* [[North Carolina Museum of Art]], Raleigh, NC.<ref>{{cite web|accessdate=2018-04-05|title=Search \u2013 Permanent Collection \u2013 NCMA \u2013 North Carolina Museum of Art|url=http://ncartmuseum.org/art/search|website=ncartmuseum.org}}</ref>\n*[[Pier 24 Photography]], San Francisco, CA.<ref>https://pier24.org/collection/</ref>\n* [[San Francisco Museum of Modern Art]], San Francisco, CA.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.sfmoma.org/artist/Todd_Hido|title=Todd Hido|website=SFMOMA|accessdate=14 December 2017}}</ref>\n* [[Whitney Museum of American Art]], NY.<ref>{{cite web|accessdate=2018-04-05|title=Whitney Museum of American Art: Todd Hido: #2663|url=http://collection.whitney.org/object/27261|website=collection.whitney.org}}</ref>\n}}\n\n== Notes ==\n<references group=\"n\" />\n\n== Sources ==\n* [http://www.clevelandart.org/educef/hido/index.aspx Berwick, Carly. Todd Hido: Julie Saul, ART news, November, pp.&nbsp;153\u2013154. 2004.]{{dead link|date=July 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=no }}\n* [http://findarticles.com/p/articles/mi_hb3202/is_200110/ai_n7879833?tag=content;col1: Helfand, Glen. Todd Hido. (Stephen Wirtz), Artforum International, October 2001.]\n* [http://findarticles.com/p/articles/mi_m0268/is_n9_v36/ai_n27533113/pg_1 Grundberg, Andy. House sitting: the photography of Todd Hido, Artforum, May 1998.]\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{official website|www.toddhido.com}}\n* [http://pier24.org/video/todd-hido-house-hunting/ Pier 24 Photography Artist Video: Todd Hido]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20131003045644/http://kadist.org/en/people/todd-hido Todd Hido] at [[Kadist Art Foundation]]\n* [http://www.ahornmagazine.com/issue_6/interview_hido/interview_hido.html Interview with Todd Hido \u2013 Ahorn Magazine, Issue 6]\n* [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=embdo2Er19A 'Working in the Vicinity of Narrative: Todd Hido and Darius Himes'] from School of Visual Arts. Hido presentation of his career (video)\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Hido, Todd}}\n[[Category:1968 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Photographers from California]]\n[[Category:20th-century American photographers]]\n[[Category:21st-century American photographers]]\n[[Category:California College of the Arts alumni]]\n[[Category:Artists from the San Francisco Bay Area]]\n[[Category:Rhode Island School of Design alumni]]\n[[Category:Tufts University alumni]]\n[[Category:Photographers from Ohio]]\n[[Category:People from Kent, Ohio]]\n[[Category:Educators from Ohio]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox artist\n| name          = Todd Hido\n| image         = Todd Hido by McCall - CC.jpg\n| caption       = Todd Hido, Montana, 2019\n| birth_name    =\n| birth_date    = {{Birth date and age|1968|08|25}}\n| birth_place   = [[Kent, Ohio]], United States\n| death_date    =\n| death_place   =\n| nationality   = [[United States|American]]\n| field         = [[Photography]]\n| education     = [[Bachelor of Fine Arts|B.F.A.]] \u2013 [[School of the Museum of Fine Arts, Boston]] <br/> [[Master of Fine Arts|M.F.A.]] \u2013 [[California College of the Arts]]\n| training      =\n| movement      =\n| works         =\n| patrons       =\n| influenced    =\n| awards        =\n| website       = {{URL|www.toddhido.com}}\n}}\n\n'''Todd Hido''' (born 25 August 1968)<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bu.edu/prc/prcpov/artists/a16.html|title=Todd Hido|website=Bu.edu|accessdate=14 December 2017}}</ref> is an American [[contemporary artist]] and photographer.<ref>{{cite web|accessdate=2018-12-03|title=Todd Hido|url=http://www.artnet.com/artists/todd-hido/|website=www.artnet.com}}</ref> He has produced 17 books,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/artanddesign/photography-blog/2013/oct/02/unseen-photo-fair-amsterdam-review|title=A window on weird: step inside the Unseen Photo fair in Amsterdam|first=Sean|last=O'Hagan|date=2 October 2013|accessdate=14 December 2017|website=Theguardian.com}}</ref> had his work exhibited widely and included in various public collections.<ref>https://www.mmoca.org/learn/teachers/teaching-pages/todd-hido</ref>\n\n== Life and work ==\nHido was born August 25, 1968, in [[Kent, Ohio]], United States, and graduated from [[Theodore Roosevelt High School (Kent, Ohio)|Theodore Roosevelt High School]] in 1986.<ref>{{cite web |title= Kent City Schools Hall of Fame archives|url=https://www.kentschools.net/hall-of-fame/hall-of-fame-archives/ |year=2009 |work=KentSchools.net |publisher=Kent City School District |accessdate=January 20, 2020}}</ref> He graduated in 1991 with a B.F.A. from [[Tufts University]],<ref>{{cite news|accessdate=December 3, 2018 |title=Todd Hido: Sources and Influences \u2013 Aperture Foundation NY|url=https://aperture.org/workshops-classes/hido-2015/|newspaper=Aperture Foundation NY}}</ref> [[Medford, Massachusetts]] and [[School of the Museum of Fine Arts, Boston]], Massachusetts. Between 1991 and 1992 he studied at [[Rhode Island School of Design]], [[Providence, Rhode Island]].<ref name=\"hido-bio\">{{cite web|url=http://www.toddhido.com/|title=Todd Hido|website=Toddhido.com|accessdate=December 14, 2017}}</ref> In 1996 he gained an M.F.A. from [[California College of Arts and Crafts]], [[Oakland, California]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cca.edu/academics/graduate/alumni|title=Graduate Alumni \u2013 California College of the Arts|website=Cca.edu|accessdate=December 14, 2017}}</ref>\n\nCurrently based in [[San Francisco]], much of Hido's earlier work involves photographs of urban and suburban housing<ref>{{cite web|url=http://designobserver.com/feature/exposure-suburban-house-at-night-by-todd-hido/39120/|title=Exposure: Surburban house at night, photographed by Todd Hido.|website=Designobserver.com |accessdate=December 14, 2017}}</ref> across the U.S.. He then started to include figures, mostly [[female nude]]s in interiors, and also to depict rural landscapes. In 2018, he released ''Bright Black World'', his first work photographed outside the U.S. with environmental overtones.\n\nHido says he is influenced by [[Alfred Hitchcock]], [[Edward Hopper]], [[Stephen Shore]], [[Robert Adams (photographer)|Robert Adams]], [[Walker Evans]], [[Nan Goldin]], [[Emmet Gowin]], [[Larry Sultan]], [[Alfred Stieglitz]], [[Andreas Gursky]] and [[Rineke Dijkstra]]. Commissioned by Italian brand [[Bottega Veneta]], he photographed actress [[Lauren Hutton]] as well as models [[Joan Smalls]] and [[Vittoria Ceretti]] for the brand's spring/summer 2017 advertisements.<ref>Alexandra Venison (January 16, 2017), [http://www.harpersbazaararabia.com/fashion/the-news/lauren-hutton-stars-in-the-bottega-veneta-springsummer2017-campaign Lauren Hutton Stars In The Bottega Veneta Spring/Summer 2017 Campaign] ''Harper's Bazaar Arabia''.</ref>\n\n== Publications ==\n=== Publications by Hido ===\n* ''House Hunting''.\n** Portland, OR: [[Nazraeli Press]], 2001. {{ISBN|978-3923922963}}.\n** Portland, OR: Nazraeli, 2007. {{ISBN|978-1590051931}}.\n* ''Outskirts''. Portland, OR: Nazraeli, 2002. {{ISBN|978-1590050286}}. Text by [[Luc Sante]]. Edition of 2000 copies.\n* ''Taft Street''. One Picture Book 6. Portland, OR: Nazraeli, 2001. {{ISBN|978-1590050170}}.\n* ''Roaming''. Portland, OR: Nazraeli, 2004. {{ISBN|978-1590050958}} Edition of 3000 copies.\n* ''Between the Two''. Portland, OR: Nazraeli, 2006. {{ISBN|978-1590051764}}. Edition of 2000 copies.\n* ''Crooked Cracked Tree in Fog''. One Picture Book 60. Portland, OR: Nazraeli, 2009. {{ISBN|978-1-59005-292-1}}. Edition of 500 copies.\n* ''Ohio.'' TBW Subscription Series #2. Oakland, CA: TBW, 2009. {{ASIN|B0087G1LD4}}. Edition of 800 copies. The other volumes are by Abner Nolan, Marianne Mueller and [[Alec Soth]].\n* ''A Road Divided''. Portland, OR: Nazraeli, 2010. {{ISBN|978-1590052662}}.\n* ''Nymph Daughters''. Kamakura: Super Labo, 2010. {{ISBN|9784905052012}}. Edition of 500 copies.\n* ''Excerpts from Silver Meadows''. Portland, OR: Nazraeli, 2013. {{ISBN|978-1590053683}}\n* ''Todd Hido on Landscapes, Interiors, and the Nude.'' The Photography Workshop Series. New York: [[Aperture Foundation|Aperture]], 2014. {{ISBN|978-1-59711-297-0}}. With an introduction by [[Gregory Halpern]].\n* ''B-Sides \u2013 Silver Meadows.'' Portland, OR: Nazraeli, 2014. {{ASIN|B00KP206DO}}. Edition of 500 copies. 50 individual cards in a clear plexi box, similar to a pack of playing cards.\n* ''Khrystyna's World.'' Amsterdam: Reflex Amsterdam, 2015. {{ISBN|978-90-71848-22-3}}. Edition of 500 copies. Published on the occasion of the exhibition, ''Todd Hido: Selections from a Survey: Khrystyna\u2019s World,'' September\u2013November 2015, Reflex Amsterdam, Amsterdam. With an essay by Katya Tylevich, \"Khrystyna's World: Detention in the Getaway Car\".<ref group=\"n\">A PDF of the book can be viewed [http://reflexamsterdam.com/wp-content/themes/newfish/pdf/todd-hido-khrystinas-world.pdf here within the Reflex Gallery website].</ref>\n* ''Seasons Road''. One Picture Book 93. Portland, OR: Nazraeli, 2016. {{ISBN|978-1-59005-456-7}}. Edition of 500 copies. 7 colour plates and 1 photographic print. \"Every year at Christmas for the past ten years, Todd Hido has traveled to Ohio to visit his parents. During his annual trip home, Hido makes photographs along the small road that serves as the namesake for this book.\"<ref>[http://www.nazraeli.com/opb/todd-hido-one-picture-book-93-seasons-road \"Todd Hido | One Picture Book #93 : Seasons Road\"] Nazraeli Press. Accessed 5 October 2016</ref>\n* ''Intimate Distance: Twenty-five Years of Photographs, A Chronological Album.'' New York: Aperture, 2016. {{ISBN|978-1-59711-360-1}}. With an essay by [[David Campany]].\n* ''B-Sides Box Sets \u2013 Homing In.'' Oakland, CA: B-Sides Box Sets, 2017. {{ISBN|978-1-5323-5128-0}}. Edition of 2000 copies. 50 individual cards in a box. Previously unpublished photographs from ''House Hunting.''\n* ''Bright Black World.'' Paso Robles, CA: Nazraeli Press, 2018. {{ISBN|978-1590054758}}. Text by Alexander Nemerov.\n\n=== Smaller publications by Hido ===\n* ''Collage Number Three.'' Deadbeat Club #41. Los Angeles, CA: Deadbeat Club, 2016.  Edition of 500 copies. 8 page zine which folds out to form a poster.\n* ''The Perfect Copy Vol. 1.'' San Francisco, CA: Colpa Press, 2016. Six 4-color [[Risograph]] photographic prints in screen printed envelope. Edition of 100 copies.\n\n=== Publications edited or with contributions by Hido ===\n* ''Witness No. 7''. Portland, OR: Nazraeli, 2009. {{ISBN|978-1590052440}}. Photographs by Hido and [[Leon Borensztein]], and photographs of images from books by various people that have inspired Hido.\n* ''Cracked Trees''. One Picture Book 59. Portland, OR: Nazraeli, 2009. {{ISBN|978-1590052914}}. Photographs by Hido, paintings by 3rd grade students. Edition of 500 copies.\n* ''Motel Club.'' Nazraeli Press Six by Six, set 1 v. 4. Portland, OR: Nazraeli, 2010. {{ISBN|1590052978}}. Edition of 100 copies. The other volumes are by [[Anthony Hernandez (photographer)|Anthony Hernandez]], [[Raymond Meeks]], [[Martin Parr]], [[Toshio Shibata]] and [[Mark Steinmetz]].\n* ''Alec Soth's Lonely Boy Mag 2: Boys and Their Cars.'' St. Paul, MN: [[Alec Soth|Little Brown Mushroom]], 2011. Edition of 1000 copies. Text and photographs by Todd Hido, [[Alec Soth]], Chad States and erotic [[diorama]]s by Peter Davidson.\n* ''One Day \u2013 10 Photographers.'' Heidelberg: [[Kehrer Verlag|Kehrer]], 2010. {{ISBN|978-3-86828-173-6}}. A boxed set of ten books of photographs taken on 21 June 2010. Edited by [[Harvey Benge]], each book by one photographer including Todd Hido, Jessica Backhaus, [[Gerry Badger]], Harvey Benge, [[John Gossage]], [[Alec Soth]], [[Rob Hornstra]], [[Rinko Kawauchi]], Eva Maria Ocherbauer and Martin Parr.<ref group=\"n\">The publisher's description of this set: {{Cite web|url=https://www.kehrerverlag.com/en/one-day-10-photographers-978-3-86828-173-6|title=One Day \u2013 Kehrer Verlag|website=Kehrer Verlag|language=en|access-date=2018-04-05}}</ref>\n* ''Here.'', San Francisco: Pier 24 Photography, 2011. {{ISBN|978-0-9839917-0-0}}. Exhibition guide.\n* ''Leon Borensztein: American Portraits 1979\u20131989.'' Portland, OR: Nazraeli, 2011. {{ISBN|978-1-59005-305-8}}. Photographs by Leon Borensztein. Edited by Hido.\n* ''About Face'', San Francisco: Pier 24 Photography, 2012. {{ISBN|978-0-9839917-1-7}}. Exhibition guide\n* ''A Sense of Place'', San Francisco: Pier 24 Photography, 2013. {{ISBN|978-0-9839917-3-1}}. Exhibition guide.\n* ''About Face.'' San Francisco: Pier 24 Photography, 2014. {{ISBN|978-0-9839917-2-4}}. Exhibition catalog. Edition of 1000 copies. With forewords by Christopher McCall, and [[Richard Avedon]] (from ''In the American West''), an introduction by [[Philip Gefter]], and texts by [[Sandra S. Phillips]], and Ulrike Schneider.\n* ''The Open Road: Photography & the American Road Trip''. Edited and with text by [[David Campany]], photographs by Hido, [[Robert Frank]], [[Ed Ruscha]], [[Inge Morath]], [[Garry Winogrand]], [[William Egglestone]], [[Lee Friedlander]], [[Joel Meyerowitz]], [[Jacob Holdt]], [[Stephen Shore]], [[Bernard Plossu]], [[Victor Burgin]], [[Joel Sternfeld]], [[Shin'ya Fujiwara]], [[Alec Soth]], [[Ryan McGinley]], [[Justine Kurland]], and Taiyo Onorato and Nico Krebs.\n** New York: [[Aperture Foundation|Aperture]], 2014. {{ISBN|978-1-59711-240-6}}.\n** ''Road Trips: Voyages photographiques \u00e0 travers l\u2019Am\u00e9rique.'' Paris: Textuel, 2014. {{ISBN|9782845975002}}. French-language version.\n** ''En la Carretera: Viajes fotogr\u00e1ficos a trav\u00e9s de Norteam\u00e9rica.'' Madrid: La F\u00e1brica, 2014. {{ISBN|9788415691822}}. Spanish-language version.\n* ''A Sense of Place'', San Francisco: Pier 24 Photography, 2015. {{ISBN|978-0-9839917-4-8}}. Exhibition catalog. Edition of 1000 copies.\n\n== Exhibitions ==\n=== Solo ===\n{{BLP sources section|date=December 2018}}\n* 1997: SF Camerawork, San Francisco, CA.\n* 1998: ''House Hunting'', Stephen Wirtz Gallery, San Francisco, CA.\n* 1999: Inman Gallery, Houston TX.\n* 2000: ''Photographs Taken at Night,'' Kohn Turner Gallery, Los Angeles, CA. Julie Saul Gallery, New York, NY.\n* 2000: ''Homing In,'' Stephen Wirtz Gallery, San Francisco, CA.\n* 2001: ''New Photographs,'' Stephen Wirtz Gallery, San Francisco, CA. Inman Gallery, Houston, TX.\n* 2002: The Cleveland Museum of Art, Cleveland, Ohio.\n* 2002: ''Open House,'' Kemper Museum of Contemporary Art.\n* 2002: ''Roaming'', Paul Morris Gallery, New York, NY. Carrie Secrist Gallery, Chicago, IL. Taft Street, 3A Garage, San Francisco, CA.\n* 2003: Baldwin Gallery, Aspen Colorado. Carrie Secrist Gallery, Chicago, IL.\n* 2004: ''Roaming-New Landscapes'', Julie Saul Gallery, New York, NY.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://query.nytimes.com/gst/fullpage.html?res=9C01EEDB153BF93BA35753C1A9629C8B63 |author=Glueck, Grace|title=Art in Review : Todd Hido \u2013 'Roaming: New Landscapes'|newspaper=[[The New York Times]]|accessdate=October 8, 2004}}</ref>\n* 2004: ''Roaming'', Stephen Wirtz Gallery, San Francisco, CA. Carrie Secrist Gallery, Chicago, IL. Michael Berger Gallery, Pittsburgh, Pennsylvania. Baldwin Gallery, Aspen, Colorado.\n* 2005 Todd Hido, Sheppard Gallery, University of Nevada, Reno, NV. Inman Gallery, Houston, TX. Karyn Lovegrove Gallery, Los Angeles, CA.\n* 2006: ''Unfinished Narratives'', Photographic Center Northwest, Seattle, WA.\n* 2007: ''Between the Two'', Stephen Wirtz Gallery, San Francisco, CA.\n* 2007: Todd Hido, Rose Gallery, Santa Monica, CA.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.space15twenty.com/todd_hidos_a_road_divided |title=Space 15 Twenty |publisher=Space 15 Twenty |date= |accessdate=2014-04-19}}</ref>\n* 2008: ''A Road Divided''; Stephen Wirtz Gallery, San Francisco, CA.\n* 2008: ''Between the Two'', Yours Gallery, Warsaw, Poland.\n* 2009: ''A Road Divided''; [[Bruce Silverstein Gallery]], New York.\n* 2010: ''Househunting'' / ''Nudes''; Kaune, Sudendorf Gallery, Cologne, Germany.\n* 2011: ''A Road Divided''; Kaune, Posnik, Spohr Gallery, Cologne, Germany.\n* 2011: ''Fragmented Narratives''; Bruce Silverstein Gallery, New York.\n* 2012:  ''I Drive...'', La Galerie Particuli\u00e8re, Paris.\n* 2013:  ''Excerpts from Silver Meadows''; Kaune, Posnik, Spohr Gallery, Cologne, Germany.\n* 2015: ''Todd Hido: Selections from a Survey''; Casemore/Kirkeby, San Francisco, California<ref name=\"cmke\">https://casemorekirkeby.com/exhibitions/</ref>\n* 2016: ''Intimate Distance''; Casemore Kirkeby, San Francisco, California<ref name=\"cmke\" />\n* 2019: ''Bright Black World''; Casemore Kirkeby, San Francisco, California<ref name=\"cmke\" />\n\n=== Group ===\n* 2004: ''Light and Atmosphere,'' [[P\u00e9rez Art Museum Miami|Miami Art Museum]], FL, April 2004 \u2013 January 2005.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.pamm.org/exhibitions/light-and-atmosphere | access-date = 16 June 2016 | publisher = [[P\u00e9rez Art Museum Miami]] | title = Light and Atmosphere}}</ref>\n* 2006\u20132007: ''Suburban Escape,'' [[San Jose Museum of Art]], San Jose, CA, September 2006 \u2013 March 2007. Work  by Hido and 29 other photographers.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://sjmusart.org/exhibition/suburban-escape-art-california-sprawl | access-date = 16 June 2016 | publisher = [[San Jose Museum of Art]] | title = Suburban Escape: The Art of California Sprawl}}</ref>\n* 2010: ''Pier 24: The Inaugural Exhibition'', [[Pier 24 Photography]], San Francisco, CA, March\u2013June 2010.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://pier24.org/exhibition/pier-24-the-inaugural-exhibition/|title=Pier 24: The Inaugural Exhibition \u2013 Pier 24|website=Pier24.org|accessdate=14 December 2017}}</ref>\n* 2010: ''Day & Night,'' Main Exhibition Copenhagen Photo Festival, Copenhagen, Denmark.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://copenhagenphotofestival.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/02/CPF-PRESS.pdf |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2016-06-13 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150915092646/http://copenhagenphotofestival.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/02/CPF-PRESS.pdf |archivedate=2015-09-15 }}</ref>\n* 2011\u20132012: ''Here''., [[Pier 24 Photography]], San Francisco, CA, May 2011 \u2013 January 2012.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://pier24.org/exhibition/here/|title=Here. - Pier 24|website=Pier24.org|accessdate=14 December 2017}}</ref>\n* 2012\u20132013: ''About Face'', [[Pier 24 Photography]], San Francisco, CA, May 2012 \u2013 April 2013.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://pier24.org/exhibition/about-face/|title=About Face \u2013 Pier 24|website=Pier24.org|accessdate=14 December 2017}}</ref>\n* 2013\u20132014: ''A Sense of Place'', [[Pier 24 Photography]], San Francisco, CA, July 2013 \u2013 May 2014.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://pier24.org/exhibition/a-sense-of-place/|title=A Sense of Place \u2013 Pier 24|website=Pier24.org|accessdate=14 December 2017}}</ref>\n* 2016: ''The Open Road: Photography and the American Road Trip,'' [[Crystal Bridges Museum of American Art]], Bentonville, AR, February\u2013May 2016.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://crystalbridges.org/the-open-road/|title=The Open Road \u2013 Crystal Bridges Museum of American Art|website=crystalbridges.org|accessdate=14 December 2017}}</ref> Curated by [[David Campany]] and Denise Wolff.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://aperture.org/traveling-exhibitions/open-road/ | access-date = 11 March 2016 | publisher = [[Aperture Foundation]] | title = The Open Road: Photography and the American Road Trip: Curated by David Campany and Denise Wolff}}</ref>\n* 2016\u20132017: ''Collected'', Pier 24 Photography, San Francisco, CA, May 2016 \u2013 January 2017.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://pier24.org/exhibitions/|title=Exhibitions \u2013 Pier 24|website=Pier24.org|accessdate=14 December 2017}}</ref>\n\n== Awards ==\n* 1996: Barclay Simpson Award, [[California College of the Arts]], CA. Joinet winner with [[Geoffrey Chadsey]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://issuu.com/californiacollegeofthearts/docs/barclay25_catalog_lowres|title=Celebrating 25 Years of the Barclay Simpson Award|website=Issuu.com|accessdate=14 December 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cca.edu/calendar/2012/barclay-simpson-award-retrospective-exhibition-1987-2012|title=We're All Here Because We're Not All There \u2013 California College of the Arts|website=Cca.edu|accessdate=14 December 2017}}</ref>\n* 1998: The Wallace Alexander Gerbode Foundation, Visual Arts Award.<ref group=\"n\">The Wallace Alexander Gerbode Foundation's \"Special Awards Recipients 1987-Present\" PDF [http://foundationcenter.org/grantmaker/gerbode/docs/1987-Present-Recipients.pdf here] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150908025301/http://www.foundationcenter.org/grantmaker/gerbode/docs/1987-Present-Recipients.pdf |date=2015-09-08 }} does not list Hido.</ref>\n* 1998: Recent Graduate of Distinction Award, California College of the Arts, CA.{{citation needed|date=October 2015}}\n* 2001: Eureka Fellowship, Fleishhacker Foundation.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.fleishhackerfoundation.org/grants/eureka-fellowship-program/1999-2001/|title=The Fleishhacker Foundation \u2013 1999\u20132001|website=Fleishhackerfoundation.org|accessdate=14 December 2017}}</ref>\n* 2002: Best First Monograph of 2001, Photo-Eye.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.photoeye.com/bookstore/citation.cfm?catalog=PK802&i=3902289015&i2=|title=photo-eye Bookstore \u2013 Architecture of Time by Hiroshi Sugimoto \u2013 photobook|website=Photoeye.com|accessdate=14 December 2017}}</ref>\n* 2017: In Focus Artist selected by the National Portrait Gallery UK curators, an annual showcase for new work by an internationally renowned photographer <ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.npg.org.uk/whatson/event-root/november/in-conversation-13112017|title=In Conversation: Todd Hido \u2013 National Portrait Gallery|website=Npg.org.uk|accessdate=14 December 2017}}</ref>\n\n== Collections ==\nHido's work is held in the following public collections:\n{{col-list|colwidth=30em|\n* [[Art Institute of Chicago]], IL.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.artic.edu/aic/collections/artwork/artist/Hido,+Todd|title=Hido, Todd \u2013 The Art Institute of Chicago|website=Artic.edu|accessdate=14 December 2017}}</ref>\n* [[Amon Carter Museum of American Art]], Fort Worth, TX.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cartermuseum.org/artworks/779|title=Untitled #2431 \u2013 Todd Hido (b. 1968)|date=6 June 2008|website=Cartermuseum.org|accessdate=14 December 2017}}</ref>\n* [[Berkeley Art Museum and Pacific Film Archive]], Berkeley, CA.<ref>{{cite web|accessdate=2018-04-05|title=This Just In: Recent Acquisitions: BAMPFA|url=https://bampfa.org/program/just-recent-acquisitions|website=bampfa.org}}</ref>\n* [[Cleveland Museum of Art]], Cleveland, OH.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.clevelandart.org/art/2003.9|title=Untitled #2421 \u2013 Cleveland Museum of Art|website=Clevelandart.org|accessdate=14 December 2017}}</ref>\n* [[Di rosa]], Napa, CA.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dirosaart.org/wp-content/uploads/2011/07/Know-the-Rules-_PR.pdf|format=PDF|title=Know the Rules \u2013 Then Break Them Photography from the di Rosa Collection|website=Dirosaart.org\\accessdate=14 December 2017}}</ref>\n* [[George Eastman House]], Rochester, NY: 6 prints.<ref>https://collections.eastman.org/people/31393/todd-hido/objects</ref>\n* [[Kemper Museum of Contemporary Art]], Kansas City, MO.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.