{"title_page": "Mid90s", "text_new": "{{short description|2018 film directed by Jonah Hill}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name           = mid90s\n| image          = Mid90s.png\n| border         = no\n| caption        = Theatrical release poster\n| director       = [[Jonah Hill]]\n| producer       = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Eli Bush]]\n* Jonah Hill \n* Ken Kao\n* [[Scott Rudin]]\n* Lila Yacoub\n}}\n| writers        = {{Plainlist|\n* Jonah Hill\n}}\n| starring       = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Sunny Suljic]]\n* [[Lucas Hedges]]\n* [[Na-Kel Smith]]\n* Olan Prenatt\n* Gio Galicia\n* Ryder McLaughlin\n* [[Alexa Demie]]\n* [[Katherine Waterston]]\n}}\n| music          = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Trent Reznor]]\n* [[Atticus Ross]]\n}}\n| cinematography = [[Christopher Blauvelt]]\n| editing        = Nick Houy\n| studio         = {{Plainlist|\n* [[A24 (company)|A24]]\n* Waypoint Entertainment\n* Scott Rudin Productions\n}}\n| distributor    = A24\n| released       = {{Film date|2018|9|9|[[Toronto International Film Festival|TIFF]]|2018|10|19|United States}}\n| runtime        = 85 minutes<ref>{{cite web|url=http://tiff.net/tiff/mid90s|title=Mid90s|website=[[Toronto International Film Festival]]|accessdate=August 14, 2018}}</ref>\n| country        = United States\n| language       = English\n| budget         = $1.7 million<ref>{{cite journal |url= https://esd.ny.gov/sites/default/files/LD%20Q3%202019%20Report.pdf |title= FILM TAX CREDIT \u2013 QUARTERLY REPORT CALENDAR YEAR 2019: THIRD QUARTER |website=[[New York State]]|page=10 |date=September 30, 2019 |accessdate=March 12, 2020}}</ref>\n| gross          = $9.3 million<ref name=\"BOM\">{{cite web|url=https://www.boxofficemojo.com/title/tt5613484/|title=Mid90s(2018)|website=[[Box Office Mojo]]|accessdate=October 30, 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"Numbers\">{{cite web|url=https://www.the-numbers.com/movie/Mid90s-(2018)#tab=summary|title=''Mid90s'' (2018)|publisher=[[The Numbers (website)|The Numbers]]|accessdate=October 16, 2019}}</ref>\n}}\n\n'''''Mid90s''''' (stylized as '''''mid90s''''') is a 2018 American [[coming-of-age story|coming-of-age]] [[comedy-drama]] film written and directed by [[Jonah Hill]], in his feature directorial debut. It stars [[Sunny Suljic]], [[Lucas Hedges]] and [[Katherine Waterston]], and follows a 13-year-old boy who begins spending time with a mostly older group of [[Skateboarding|skateboarders]] while living in 1990s [[Los Angeles]].\n\nThe film had its world premiere at the [[2018 Toronto International Film Festival|Toronto International Film Festival]] on September 9, 2018 and was theatrically released in the United States on October 19, 2018, by [[A24 (company)|A24]]. It was well received by critics, who called it a \"promising first outing for Hill\u201d, and praised the sense of nostalgia.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://editorial.rottentomatoes.com/article/hunter-killer-is-substandard/|title=''Hunter Killer'' Is Substandard |first=Ryan|last=Fujitani|website=[[Rotten Tomatoes]]|date=October 25, 2018|accessdate=October 26, 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Plot==\nIn 1996, 13-year-old Stevie lives in [[Palms, Los Angeles|Palms]], [[Los Angeles]] with his abusive older brother Ian and single mother Dabney. One day Stevie bikes past Motor Avenue Skateshop, admires the boastful camaraderie of the skateboarders outside, and returns the following day. Back home, he trades with his brother for a skateboard, brings it to the shop and befriends young skater Ruben, who introduces him to the rest of the group: Ray, \"Fuckshit\", and \"Fourth Grade\". Although an inexperienced skater, Stevie is drawn to the group and aspires to imitate their [[Stunt performer|daredevil]] behavior and [[anti-social behaviour|anti-social]] attitudes. b\n\nWhile attempting a skateboard leap across an open section between two rooftops, Stevie falls and suffers a head injury. Dabney becomes concerned about his turn towards recklessness and his new friends, but Stevie has already made up his mind that he is sticking with the group. Ian has a tense standoff with Fuckshit as Stevie watches, but Ian appears intimidated by the group and leaves before a fight can break out. Stevie begins smoking, drinking, and experimenting with [[marijuana]]. At a party, he has his first sexual experience.\n\nAfter Stevie comes home intoxicated, he and Ian get into a violent fight. Ian has an emotional breakdown when Stevie says that he has no friends and, following the conflict, a distressed Stevie attempts to [[Asphyxia|asphyxiate]] himself with a cord from a [[Super Nintendo]] controller, one of several self-harm incidents. The next day, Dabney forbids Stevie from hanging out with the boys. Stevie lashes out and refuses to obey. Having alienated his mother and brother, Stevie sits alone behind the skate shop. Ray consoles Stevie, telling him that even though he thinks his life is bad, the other boys have it worse: Fourth Grade is poor to the point of not being able to afford socks, Ruben's mom is a drug addict, Fuckshit's reckless partying is worsening, and Ray lost his younger brother, who was hit by a car. Ray then takes Stevie out to skate at night and they fall asleep in a park.\n\nThe shop hosts a party in back of the store. Ray hopes to make a career in skating, and chats up two professionals as potential sponsors. Fuckshit, who is drunk and high, tries to sabotage Ray's chances by embarrassing him in front of the pros. Stevie, who has been drinking heavily, is provoked into a brawl with Ruben. Discouraged by the undisciplined behavior of his friends, Ray tells everyone to go home. However, Fuckshit insists on driving the group to another party. Ray reluctantly agrees, and the group head off, with Stevie riding shotgun. No one seems happy except Fuckshit, whose judgment has been impaired by drugs and alcohol. Talking animatedly and driving inattentively, Fuckshit crashes and flips the car on its side. Stevie is knocked unconscious and is rushed to the hospital. \n\nStevie later awakens in a hospital bed, and sees Ian in a chair alongside him. Ian gives Stevie a container of orange juice to comfort his little brother. Dabney enters the hospital and sees Stevie's friends, asleep in the waiting room. Moved by the fact they are there for Stevie, Dabney encourages them to visit Stevie's room. They appear willing to reconcile with each other after the previous night's events. Fourth Grade, who has been filming their adventures throughout the film, says he has something to show them. He plugs his camera into a TV to play them an edited vide6, and a few days. I have a good idea to have a good idea to have a good idea to have a good idea to have a good idea to have a good idea to have a good idea to have a good idea 555555, and I will be a good idea to have a good idea to have a good idea\n\n==Cast==\n* [[Sunny Suljic]] as Stevie \"Sunburn\"\n* [[Na-Kel Smith]] as Ray\n* Olan Prenatt as Fuckshit\n* [[Lucas Hedges]] as Ian, Stevie's brother\n* [[Katherine Waterston]] as Dabney, Ian and Stevie's mother\n* Gio Galicia as Ruben\n* Ryder McLaughlin as Fourth Grade\n* [[Alexa Demie]] as Estee\nAdditionally, [[Jerrod Carmichael]] cameos as a security guard whom Stevie and his friends taunt. Filmmaker [[Harmony Korine]] appears briefly as a sexual partner of Dabney. Korine wrote the screenplay for the 1995 film ''[[Kids (film)|Kids]]'', which Hill cited as the reason for his cameo appearance.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Ahearn |first1=Victoria |title=Jonah Hill on including \u2018toxic masculinity\u2019 in directorial debut Mid90s |url=https://www.thestar.com/entertainment/2018/10/24/jonah-hill-on-including-toxic-masculinity-in-directorial-debut-mid90s.html |accessdate=2 June 2019 |work=Toronto Star |date=25 October 2018 |language=en}}</ref> Hip-hop artist [[Del the Funky Homosapien]] and professional skateboarder [[Chad Muska]] appear as homeless man #1 and #2 respectively.\n\n==Production==\nOn March 30, 2016, it was announced that [[Jonah Hill]] would be making his directorial debut from his own [[spec script]], ''Mid90s'', a film he would not appear in.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://deadline.com/2016/03/jonah-hill-sets-his-spec-script-mid-90s-as-directorial-debut-1201728992/|title=Jonah Hill To Helm \u2018Mid 90s\u2019 From His Spec Script In Feature Directorial Debut|last=Lincoln|first=Ross A.|date=2016-03-31|work=Deadline|access-date=2017-07-16|language=en-US}}</ref> \n\nIn March 2017, [[Lucas Hedges]] joined the cast.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://thefilmstage.com/news/jonah-hills-directorial-debut-mid-90s-to-reunite-manchester-by-the-sea-stars/|title=Jonah Hill\u2019s Directorial Debut \u2018Mid \u201990s\u2019 to Reunite \u2018Manchester by the Sea\u2019 Stars|date=2017-03-01|work=The Film Stage|access-date=2017-07-16|language=en-US}}</ref> In July 2017, it was reported that [[Katherine Waterston]] had signed on and that [[Sunny Suljic]] was cast in the lead role. It was also revealed that principal production on the film had commenced.<ref name=\"WaterstonSuljicCast\">{{Cite news|url=http://www.tracking-board.com/katherine-waterston-sunny-suljic-in-talks-to-star-in-jonah-hills-directorial-debut-mid-90s-exclusive/|title=Katherine Waterston, Sunny Suljic to Star in Jonah Hill\u2019s Directorial Debut \u201cMid-90s\u201d (Exclusive)|date=2017-07-14|work=The Tracking Board|access-date=2017-07-16|language=en-US}}</ref> On August 1, 2017, [[Alexa Demie]] joined the cast.<ref name=\"DemieCast\">{{Cite news|url=https://deadline.com/2017/08/alexa-demie-jonah-hill-mid-90s-tommy-dorfman-fluidity-1202140150/|title=Alexa Demie Set For Jonah Hill\u2019s \u2018Mid \u201990s\u2019; Tommy Dorfman Cast In \u2018Fluidity\u2019|date=2017-08-02|work=Deadline|access-date=2017-08-02|language=en-US}}</ref>\n\n===Music===\n{{Main|Mid90s (soundtrack)}}\n\n''Mid90s'' features an original score by [[Trent Reznor]] and [[Atticus Ross]], as well as recordings by [[Pixies (band)|Pixies]], [[Morrissey]], [[Herbie Hancock]], [[ESG (band)|ESG]], [[the Mamas and the Papas]], [[Souls of Mischief]], [[Nirvana (band)|Nirvana]], and various [[1990 in hip hop music|1990s hip hop music]].\n\n==Release==\n''Mid90s'' had its world premiere at the [[Toronto International Film Festival]] on September 9, 2018,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.screendaily.com/news/toronto-unveils-contemporary-world-cinema-more-galas-and-special-presentations-/5131634.article|title=Toronto unveils Contemporary World Cinema, more Galas and Special Presentations|website=[[Screen International]]|first=Jeremy|last=Kay|date=August 14, 2018|accessdate=August 14, 2018}}</ref> and was also screened at the [[New York Film Festival]] on October 7, 2018.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.filmlinc.org/nyff2018/films/mid90s/|title=Mid90s|website=[[New York Film Festival]]|accessdate=October 1, 2018}}</ref> It was theatrically released in the United States on October 19, 2018, in limited engagements, with a wide release the following weekend.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://collider.com/mid90s-trailer-jonah-hill/|title=\u2018Mid90s\u2019 Trailer: Jonah Hill\u2019s Directorial Debut Takes a NSFW Dive into L.A. Skate Culture|website=[[Collider]]|first=Matt|last=Goldberg|date=July 24, 2018|accessdate=July 24, 2018}}</ref> Altitude has announced that ''Mid90s'' is being released in UK and Irish cinemas on April 12, 2019.<ref name=\"Filmoria\">{{cite web |url=https://www.filmoria.co.uk/mid90s-in-cinemas-nationwide-on-12-april-2019-2 |title=Mid90s in UK and Irish cinemas on 12 April 2019 |publisher=Filmoria.co.uk |date= |accessdate=20 March 2019}}</ref>{{update inline|date=August 2019}}\n\n===Home media===\n''Mid90s'' was released on DVD and Blu-ray on January 8, 2019.<ref>https://www.irishfilmcritic.com/mid90s-arrives-on-blu-ray-dvd-on-demand-january-8/</ref>\n\n==Reception==\n===Box office===\n''Mid90s'' grossed $249,500 from four theaters in its opening weekend for an average of $62,375 per venue, good for the third best of 2018.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2018/10/halloween-record-opening-weekend-box-office-1202485871/|title=\u2018Halloween\u2019 Scares Up Second-Best October Opening With $77M+; Best Debut For Blumhouse & Carpenter Canon; Great Launch For Miramax|website=[[Deadline Hollywood]]|publisher=[[Penske Business Media]]|date=October 21, 2018 |first=Anthony |last= D'Alessandro|accessdate=October 21, 2018}}</ref> It expanded to 1,206 theaters the following week and made $3 million, finishing 10th at the box office.<ref name=\"Dead2\">{{cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2018/10/halloween-screaming-a-33m-second-weekend-will-slash-100m-mark-tonight-1202490458/|title=\u2018Halloween\u2019 Screams $32M Second Weekend As October B.O. Moves Toward Record|website=[[Deadline Hollywood]]|publisher=[[Penske Business Media]]|date=October 28, 2018 |first=Anthony |last= D'Alessandro|accessdate=October 28, 2018}}</ref> In its third weekend of release the film made $1.36 million.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2018/11/boy-erased-makes-its-mark-with-robust-bow-a-private-war-aims-ok-can-you-ever-forgive-me-solid-in-expansion-specialty-box-office-1202495753/|title=\u2018Boy Erased\u2019 With Robust Bow; \u2018A Private War\u2019 Aims OK: Specialty Box Office|website=[[Deadline Hollywood]]|publisher=[[Penske Business Media]]|date=November 4, 2018 |first=Brian |last= Brooks|accessdate=November 4, 2018}}</ref>\n\n===Critical response===\nOn [[review aggregator]] [[Rotten Tomatoes]], the film holds an approval rating of 81% based on 216 reviews, with an average rating of 7.1/10. The website's critical consensus reads, \"''Mid90s'' tells a clear-eyed yet nostalgic coming-of-age tale that might mark the start of an auspicious new career for debuting writer-director Jonah Hill.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/mid90s|title=Mid90s (2018)|work=[[Rotten Tomatoes]]|publisher=[[Fandango Media]]|accessdate=September 1, 2019}}</ref> On [[Metacritic]], the film has a weighted average score of 67 out of 100, based on 41 critics, indicating \"generally favorable reviews\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.metacritic.com/movie/mid90s|title=Mid90s reviews|website=[[Metacritic]]|accessdate=November 3, 2018}}</ref> Audiences polled by [[PostTrak]] gave the film an 83% overall positive score and a 62% \"definite recommend\".<ref name=\"Dead2\"/>\n\n[[Owen Gleiberman]] of ''[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]'' called the film \"a coming-of-age tale that's unvarnished enough to believe,\" specifying, \"the fact that a star like Hill built this movie from the ground up, and did it with so much integrity and flair, lends it an undeniable hipster quotient.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://variety.com/2018/film/reviews/mid90s-review-jonah-hill-1202934291/|title=Film Review: \u2018mid90s\u2019|first=Owen|last=Gleiberman|date=September 10, 2018|work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|accessdate=October 26, 2018}}</ref> Writing for ''[[The Hollywood Reporter]]'', John DeFore said, \"in emotional punch and shoulda-seen-this-coming skill, it is more like Hill's ''[[Lady Bird (film)|Lady Bird]]'', a gem that feels simultaneously informed by its author's adolescence and the product of a serious artist's observational distance.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/review/mid90s-review-1141434|title='Mid90s': Film Review - TIFF 2018|author=John DeFore|date=September 9, 2018|work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]|accessdate=October 26, 2018}}</ref>\n\n[[Michael Phillips (critic)|Michael Phillips]] of the ''[[Chicago Tribune]]'' gave the film 2 out of 4 stars and said, \"Vivid in bits and pieces, ''Mid90s'' feels like a research scrapbook for a movie, not a movie. The more Hill throws you around in the name of creating a harsh, immediate impression, the more the impressions blur. Hill will make far better pictures: As an actor, it took him a few films after ''[[Superbad (film)|Superbad]]'' to discover the payoff in doing less, and less obviously. The director in him may need another project to figure that out, whatever story he tells next.\"<ref>{{cite news |last1=Phillips |first1=Michael |authorlink=Michael Phillips (critic) |title='Mid90s' review: Jonah Hill's LA story smells like teen spirit |url=https://www.chicagotribune.com/entertainment/movies/sc-mov-mid-90s-rev-1023-story.html |accessdate=October 23, 2018 |work=[[Chicago Tribune]] |date=October 27, 2018}}</ref>\n\n===Accolades===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Award\n! Category\n! Subject\n! Result\n|-\n|[[Berlin International Film Festival]]\n|Teddy Award for Best Feature Film\n|[[Jonah Hill]]\n|{{nom}}\n|-\n|[[Critics' Choice Movie Awards|Critics' Choice Movie Award]]\n|[[Critics' Choice Movie Award for Best Young Performer|Best Young Performer]]\n|[[Sunny Suljic]]\n|{{nom}}\n|-\n|Central Ohio Film Critics Association Award\n|Actor of the Year\n|[[Lucas Hedges]]\n|{{nom}}\n|-\n|[[Independent Spirit Awards|Independent Spirit Award]]\n|[[Independent Spirit Award for Best Editing|Best Editing]]\n|Nick Houy\n|{{Nominated}}\n|-\n|[[National Board of Review|NBR Award]]\n|colspan=2|[[National Board of Review: Top Ten Independent Films|Top Ten Independent Films]]\n|{{won}}\n|-\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Official website}}\n*{{IMDb title|5613484}}\n\n\n[[Category:A24 films]]\n[[Category:American films]]\n[[Category:American comedy-drama films]]\n[[Category:American coming-of-age films]]\n[[Category:Hood films]]\n[[Category:Skateboarding films]]\n[[Category:2010s coming-of-age films]]\n[[Category:Coming-of-age comedy films]]\n[[Category:Coming-of-age drama films]]\n[[Category:2018 directorial debut films]]\n[[Category:English-language films]]\n[[Category:Films produced by Jonah Hill]]\n[[Category:Films produced by Scott Rudin]]\n[[Category:Films scored by Trent Reznor]]\n[[Category:Films scored by Atticus Ross]]\n[[Category:Films about drugs]]\n[[Category:Films set in the 1990s]] \n[[Category:Films set in Los Angeles]]\n[[Category:Films shot in Los Angeles]] \n[[Category:Films with screenplays by Jonah Hill]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|2018 film directed by Jonah Hill}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name           = mid90s\n| image          = Mid90s.png\n| border         = no\n| caption        = Theatrical release poster\n| director       = [[Jonah Hill]]\n| producer       = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Eli Bush]]\n* Jonah Hill \n* Ken Kao\n* [[Scott Rudin]]\n* Lila Yacoub\n}}\n| writers        = {{Plainlist|\n* Jonah Hill\n}}\n| starring       = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Sunny Suljic]]\n* [[Lucas Hedges]]\n* [[Na-Kel Smith]]\n* Olan Prenatt\n* Gio Galicia\n* Ryder McLaughlin\n* [[Alexa Demie]]\n* [[Katherine Waterston]]\n}}\n| music          = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Trent Reznor]]\n* [[Atticus Ross]]\n}}\n| cinematography = [[Christopher Blauvelt]]\n| editing        = Nick Houy\n| studio         = {{Plainlist|\n* [[A24 (company)|A24]]\n* Waypoint Entertainment\n* Scott Rudin Productions\n}}\n| distributor    = A24\n| released       = {{Film date|2018|9|9|[[Toronto International Film Festival|TIFF]]|2018|10|19|United States}}\n| runtime        = 85 minutes<ref>{{cite web|url=http://tiff.net/tiff/mid90s|title=Mid90s|website=[[Toronto International Film Festival]]|accessdate=August 14, 2018}}</ref>\n| country        = United States\n| language       = English\n| budget         = $1.7 million<ref>{{cite journal |url= https://esd.ny.gov/sites/default/files/LD%20Q3%202019%20Report.pdf |title= FILM TAX CREDIT \u2013 QUARTERLY REPORT CALENDAR YEAR 2019: THIRD QUARTER |website=[[New York State]]|page=10 |date=September 30, 2019 |accessdate=March 12, 2020}}</ref>\n| gross          = $9.3 million<ref name=\"BOM\">{{cite web|url=https://www.boxofficemojo.com/title/tt5613484/|title=Mid90s(2018)|website=[[Box Office Mojo]]|accessdate=October 30, 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"Numbers\">{{cite web|url=https://www.the-numbers.com/movie/Mid90s-(2018)#tab=summary|title=''Mid90s'' (2018)|publisher=[[The Numbers (website)|The Numbers]]|accessdate=October 16, 2019}}</ref>\n}}\n\n'''''Mid90s''''' (stylized as '''''mid90s''''') is a 2018 American [[coming-of-age story|coming-of-age]] [[comedy-drama]] film written and directed by [[Jonah Hill]], in his feature directorial debut. It stars [[Sunny Suljic]], [[Lucas Hedges]] and [[Katherine Waterston]], and follows a 13-year-old boy who begins spending time with a mostly older group of [[Skateboarding|skateboarders]] while living in 1990s [[Los Angeles]].\n\nThe film had its world premiere at the [[2018 Toronto International Film Festival|Toronto International Film Festival]] on September 9, 2018 and was theatrically released in the United States on October 19, 2018, by [[A24 (company)|A24]]. It was well received by critics, who called it a \"promising first outing for Hill\u201d, and praised the sense of nostalgia.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://editorial.rottentomatoes.com/article/hunter-killer-is-substandard/|title=''Hunter Killer'' Is Substandard |first=Ryan|last=Fujitani|website=[[Rotten Tomatoes]]|date=October 25, 2018|accessdate=October 26, 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Plot==\nIn 1996, 13-year-old Stevie lives in [[Palms, Los Angeles|Palms]], [[Los Angeles]] with his abusive older brother Ian and single mother Dabney. One day Stevie bikes past Motor Avenue Skateshop, admires the boastful camaraderie of the skateboarders outside, and returns the following day. Back home, he trades with his brother for a skateboard, brings it to the shop and befriends young skater Ruben, who introduces him to the rest of the group: Ray, \"Fuckshit\", and \"Fourth Grade\". Although an inexperienced skater, Stevie is drawn to the group and aspires to imitate their [[Stunt performer|daredevil]] behavior and [[anti-social behaviour|anti-social]] attitudes. Stevie is nicknamed \"Sunburn\" by Ray during a conversation, and his acceptance into the group causes Ruben to resent him.\n\nWhile attempting a skateboard leap across an open section between two rooftops, Stevie falls and suffers a head injury. Dabney becomes concerned about his turn towards recklessness and his new friends, but Stevie has already made up his mind that he is sticking with the group. Ian has a tense standoff with Fuckshit as Stevie watches, but Ian appears intimidated by the group and leaves before a fight can break out. Stevie begins smoking, drinking, and experimenting with [[marijuana]]. At a party, he has his first sexual experience.\n\nAfter Stevie comes home intoxicated, he and Ian get into a violent fight. Ian has an emotional breakdown when Stevie says that he has no friends and, following the conflict, a distressed Stevie attempts to [[Asphyxia|asphyxiate]] himself with a cord from a [[Super Nintendo]] controller, one of several self-harm incidents. The next day, Dabney forbids Stevie from hanging out with the boys. Stevie lashes out and refuses to obey. Having alienated his mother and brother, Stevie sits alone behind the skate shop. Ray consoles Stevie, telling him that even though he thinks his life is bad, the other boys have it worse: Fourth Grade is poor to the point of not being able to afford socks, Ruben's mom is a drug addict, Fuckshit's reckless partying is worsening, and Ray lost his younger brother, who was hit by a car. Ray then takes Stevie out to skate at night and they fall asleep in a park.\n\nThe shop hosts a party in back of the store. Ray hopes to make a career in skating, and chats up two professionals as potential sponsors. Fuckshit, who is drunk and high, tries to sabotage Ray's chances by embarrassing him in front of the pros. Stevie, who has been drinking heavily, is provoked into a brawl with Ruben. Discouraged by the undisciplined behavior of his friends, Ray tells everyone to go home. However, Fuckshit insists on driving the group to another party. Ray reluctantly agrees, and the group head off, with Stevie riding shotgun. No one seems happy except Fuckshit, whose judgment has been impaired by drugs and alcohol. Talking animatedly and driving inattentively, Fuckshit crashes and flips the car on its side. Stevie is knocked unconscious and is rushed to the hospital. \n\nStevie later awakens in a hospital bed, and sees Ian in a chair alongside him. Ian gives Stevie a container of orange juice to comfort his little brother. Dabney enters the hospital and sees Stevie's friends, asleep in the waiting room. Moved by the fact they are there for Stevie, Dabney encourages them to visit Stevie's room. They appear willing to reconcile with each other after the previous night's events. Fourth Grade, who has been filming their adventures throughout the film, says he has something to show them. He plugs his camera into a TV to play them an edited video of their daily activities. Fourth Grade has titled the film \"''Mid90s''.\"\n\n==Cast==\n* [[Sunny Suljic]] as Stevie \"Sunburn\"\n* [[Na-Kel Smith]] as Ray\n* Olan Prenatt as Fuckshit\n* [[Lucas Hedges]] as Ian, Stevie's brother\n* [[Katherine Waterston]] as Dabney, Ian and Stevie's mother\n* Gio Galicia as Ruben\n* Ryder McLaughlin as Fourth Grade\n* [[Alexa Demie]] as Estee\nAdditionally, [[Jerrod Carmichael]] cameos as a security guard whom Stevie and his friends taunt. Filmmaker [[Harmony Korine]] appears briefly as a sexual partner of Dabney. Korine wrote the screenplay for the 1995 film ''[[Kids (film)|Kids]]'', which Hill cited as the reason for his cameo appearance.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Ahearn |first1=Victoria |title=Jonah Hill on including \u2018toxic masculinity\u2019 in directorial debut Mid90s |url=https://www.thestar.com/entertainment/2018/10/24/jonah-hill-on-including-toxic-masculinity-in-directorial-debut-mid90s.html |accessdate=2 June 2019 |work=Toronto Star |date=25 October 2018 |language=en}}</ref> Hip-hop artist [[Del the Funky Homosapien]] and professional skateboarder [[Chad Muska]] appear as homeless man #1 and #2 respectively.\n\n==Production==\nOn March 30, 2016, it was announced that [[Jonah Hill]] would be making his directorial debut from his own [[spec script]], ''Mid90s'', a film he would not appear in.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://deadline.com/2016/03/jonah-hill-sets-his-spec-script-mid-90s-as-directorial-debut-1201728992/|title=Jonah Hill To Helm \u2018Mid 90s\u2019 From His Spec Script In Feature Directorial Debut|last=Lincoln|first=Ross A.|date=2016-03-31|work=Deadline|access-date=2017-07-16|language=en-US}}</ref> \n\nIn March 2017, [[Lucas Hedges]] joined the cast.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://thefilmstage.com/news/jonah-hills-directorial-debut-mid-90s-to-reunite-manchester-by-the-sea-stars/|title=Jonah Hill\u2019s Directorial Debut \u2018Mid \u201990s\u2019 to Reunite \u2018Manchester by the Sea\u2019 Stars|date=2017-03-01|work=The Film Stage|access-date=2017-07-16|language=en-US}}</ref> In July 2017, it was reported that [[Katherine Waterston]] had signed on and that [[Sunny Suljic]] was cast in the lead role. It was also revealed that principal production on the film had commenced.<ref name=\"WaterstonSuljicCast\">{{Cite news|url=http://www.tracking-board.com/katherine-waterston-sunny-suljic-in-talks-to-star-in-jonah-hills-directorial-debut-mid-90s-exclusive/|title=Katherine Waterston, Sunny Suljic to Star in Jonah Hill\u2019s Directorial Debut \u201cMid-90s\u201d (Exclusive)|date=2017-07-14|work=The Tracking Board|access-date=2017-07-16|language=en-US}}</ref> On August 1, 2017, [[Alexa Demie]] joined the cast.<ref name=\"DemieCast\">{{Cite news|url=https://deadline.com/2017/08/alexa-demie-jonah-hill-mid-90s-tommy-dorfman-fluidity-1202140150/|title=Alexa Demie Set For Jonah Hill\u2019s \u2018Mid \u201990s\u2019; Tommy Dorfman Cast In \u2018Fluidity\u2019|date=2017-08-02|work=Deadline|access-date=2017-08-02|language=en-US}}</ref>\n\n===Music===\n{{Main|Mid90s (soundtrack)}}\n\n''Mid90s'' features an original score by [[Trent Reznor]] and [[Atticus Ross]], as well as recordings by [[Pixies (band)|Pixies]], [[Morrissey]], [[Herbie Hancock]], [[ESG (band)|ESG]], [[the Mamas and the Papas]], [[Souls of Mischief]], [[Nirvana (band)|Nirvana]], and various [[1990 in hip hop music|1990s hip hop music]].\n\n==Release==\n''Mid90s'' had its world premiere at the [[Toronto International Film Festival]] on September 9, 2018,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.screendaily.com/news/toronto-unveils-contemporary-world-cinema-more-galas-and-special-presentations-/5131634.article|title=Toronto unveils Contemporary World Cinema, more Galas and Special Presentations|website=[[Screen International]]|first=Jeremy|last=Kay|date=August 14, 2018|accessdate=August 14, 2018}}</ref> and was also screened at the [[New York Film Festival]] on October 7, 2018.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.filmlinc.org/nyff2018/films/mid90s/|title=Mid90s|website=[[New York Film Festival]]|accessdate=October 1, 2018}}</ref> It was theatrically released in the United States on October 19, 2018, in limited engagements, with a wide release the following weekend.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://collider.com/mid90s-trailer-jonah-hill/|title=\u2018Mid90s\u2019 Trailer: Jonah Hill\u2019s Directorial Debut Takes a NSFW Dive into L.A. Skate Culture|website=[[Collider]]|first=Matt|last=Goldberg|date=July 24, 2018|accessdate=July 24, 2018}}</ref> Altitude has announced that ''Mid90s'' is being released in UK and Irish cinemas on April 12, 2019.<ref name=\"Filmoria\">{{cite web |url=https://www.filmoria.co.uk/mid90s-in-cinemas-nationwide-on-12-april-2019-2 |title=Mid90s in UK and Irish cinemas on 12 April 2019 |publisher=Filmoria.co.uk |date= |accessdate=20 March 2019}}</ref>{{update inline|date=August 2019}}\n\n===Home media===\n''Mid90s'' was released on DVD and Blu-ray on January 8, 2019.<ref>https://www.irishfilmcritic.com/mid90s-arrives-on-blu-ray-dvd-on-demand-january-8/</ref>\n\n==Reception==\n===Box office===\n''Mid90s'' grossed $249,500 from four theaters in its opening weekend for an average of $62,375 per venue, good for the third best of 2018.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2018/10/halloween-record-opening-weekend-box-office-1202485871/|title=\u2018Halloween\u2019 Scares Up Second-Best October Opening With $77M+; Best Debut For Blumhouse & Carpenter Canon; Great Launch For Miramax|website=[[Deadline Hollywood]]|publisher=[[Penske Business Media]]|date=October 21, 2018 |first=Anthony |last= D'Alessandro|accessdate=October 21, 2018}}</ref> It expanded to 1,206 theaters the following week and made $3 million, finishing 10th at the box office.<ref name=\"Dead2\">{{cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2018/10/halloween-screaming-a-33m-second-weekend-will-slash-100m-mark-tonight-1202490458/|title=\u2018Halloween\u2019 Screams $32M Second Weekend As October B.O. Moves Toward Record|website=[[Deadline Hollywood]]|publisher=[[Penske Business Media]]|date=October 28, 2018 |first=Anthony |last= D'Alessandro|accessdate=October 28, 2018}}</ref> In its third weekend of release the film made $1.36 million.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2018/11/boy-erased-makes-its-mark-with-robust-bow-a-private-war-aims-ok-can-you-ever-forgive-me-solid-in-expansion-specialty-box-office-1202495753/|title=\u2018Boy Erased\u2019 With Robust Bow; \u2018A Private War\u2019 Aims OK: Specialty Box Office|website=[[Deadline Hollywood]]|publisher=[[Penske Business Media]]|date=November 4, 2018 |first=Brian |last= Brooks|accessdate=November 4, 2018}}</ref>\n\n===Critical response===\nOn [[review aggregator]] [[Rotten Tomatoes]], the film holds an approval rating of 81% based on 216 reviews, with an average rating of 7.1/10. The website's critical consensus reads, \"''Mid90s'' tells a clear-eyed yet nostalgic coming-of-age tale that might mark the start of an auspicious new career for debuting writer-director Jonah Hill.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/mid90s|title=Mid90s (2018)|work=[[Rotten Tomatoes]]|publisher=[[Fandango Media]]|accessdate=September 1, 2019}}</ref> On [[Metacritic]], the film has a weighted average score of 67 out of 100, based on 41 critics, indicating \"generally favorable reviews\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.metacritic.com/movie/mid90s|title=Mid90s reviews|website=[[Metacritic]]|accessdate=November 3, 2018}}</ref> Audiences polled by [[PostTrak]] gave the film an 83% overall positive score and a 62% \"definite recommend\".<ref name=\"Dead2\"/>\n\n[[Owen Gleiberman]] of ''[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]'' called the film \"a coming-of-age tale that's unvarnished enough to believe,\" specifying, \"the fact that a star like Hill built this movie from the ground up, and did it with so much integrity and flair, lends it an undeniable hipster quotient.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://variety.com/2018/film/reviews/mid90s-review-jonah-hill-1202934291/|title=Film Review: \u2018mid90s\u2019|first=Owen|last=Gleiberman|date=September 10, 2018|work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|accessdate=October 26, 2018}}</ref> Writing for ''[[The Hollywood Reporter]]'', John DeFore said, \"in emotional punch and shoulda-seen-this-coming skill, it is more like Hill's ''[[Lady Bird (film)|Lady Bird]]'', a gem that feels simultaneously informed by its author's adolescence and the product of a serious artist's observational distance.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/review/mid90s-review-1141434|title='Mid90s': Film Review - TIFF 2018|author=John DeFore|date=September 9, 2018|work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]|accessdate=October 26, 2018}}</ref>\n\n[[Michael Phillips (critic)|Michael Phillips]] of the ''[[Chicago Tribune]]'' gave the film 2 out of 4 stars and said, \"Vivid in bits and pieces, ''Mid90s'' feels like a research scrapbook for a movie, not a movie. The more Hill throws you around in the name of creating a harsh, immediate impression, the more the impressions blur. Hill will make far better pictures: As an actor, it took him a few films after ''[[Superbad (film)|Superbad]]'' to discover the payoff in doing less, and less obviously. The director in him may need another project to figure that out, whatever story he tells next.\"<ref>{{cite news |last1=Phillips |first1=Michael |authorlink=Michael Phillips (critic) |title='Mid90s' review: Jonah Hill's LA story smells like teen spirit |url=https://www.chicagotribune.com/entertainment/movies/sc-mov-mid-90s-rev-1023-story.html |accessdate=October 23, 2018 |work=[[Chicago Tribune]] |date=October 27, 2018}}</ref>\n\n===Accolades===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Award\n! Category\n! Subject\n! Result\n|-\n|[[Berlin International Film Festival]]\n|Teddy Award for Best Feature Film\n|[[Jonah Hill]]\n|{{nom}}\n|-\n|[[Critics' Choice Movie Awards|Critics' Choice Movie Award]]\n|[[Critics' Choice Movie Award for Best Young Performer|Best Young Performer]]\n|[[Sunny Suljic]]\n|{{nom}}\n|-\n|Central Ohio Film Critics Association Award\n|Actor of the Year\n|[[Lucas Hedges]]\n|{{nom}}\n|-\n|[[Independent Spirit Awards|Independent Spirit Award]]\n|[[Independent Spirit Award for Best Editing|Best Editing]]\n|Nick Houy\n|{{Nominated}}\n|-\n|[[National Board of Review|NBR Award]]\n|colspan=2|[[National Board of Review: Top Ten Independent Films|Top Ten Independent Films]]\n|{{won}}\n|-\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Official website}}\n*{{IMDb title|5613484}}\n\n\n[[Category:A24 films]]\n[[Category:American films]]\n[[Category:American comedy-drama films]]\n[[Category:American coming-of-age films]]\n[[Category:Hood films]]\n[[Category:Skateboarding films]]\n[[Category:2010s coming-of-age films]]\n[[Category:Coming-of-age comedy films]]\n[[Category:Coming-of-age drama films]]\n[[Category:2018 directorial debut films]]\n[[Category:English-language films]]\n[[Category:Films produced by Jonah Hill]]\n[[Category:Films produced by Scott Rudin]]\n[[Category:Films scored by Trent Reznor]]\n[[Category:Films scored by Atticus Ross]]\n[[Category:Films about drugs]]\n[[Category:Films set in the 1990s]] \n[[Category:Films set in Los Angeles]]\n[[Category:Films shot in Los Angeles]] \n[[Category:Films with screenplays by Jonah Hill]]\n", "name_user": "2001:56a:77e9:2400:e5e0:c28c:d443:b036", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(\u2192\u200ePlot)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mid90s"}
{"title_page": "Koharu Kusumi", "text_new": "{{Infobox person\n| name               = Koharu Kusumi\n| image              = <!-- filename only, no \"File:\" or \"Image:\" prefix, and no enclosing [[brackets]] -->\n| alt                = <!-- descriptive text for use by speech synthesis (text-to-speech) software -->\n| caption            = \n| native_name        = \u4e45\u4f4f \u5c0f\u6625\n| native_name_lang   = ja\n| birth_name         = <!-- only use if different from name -->\n| birth_date         = {{birth date and age|1992|7|15}}<ref name=\"oricon profile\">{{cite web | url=https://www.oricon.co.jp/prof/386555/profile/ | title=\u4e45\u4f4f\u5c0f\u6625\u306e\u30d7\u30ed\u30d5\u30a3\u30fc\u30eb | trans-title=Koharu Kusumi's profile | work=[[Oricon]] | language=ja | accessdate=2020-01-20}}</ref>\n| birth_place        = [[Niigata Prefecture]], Japan<ref name=\"oricon profile\"/>\n| death_date         = <!-- {{Death date and age|YYYY|MM|DD|YYYY|MM|DD}} (death date then birth date)  -->\n| death_place        = \n| nationality        = \n| other_names        = \n| occupation         = {{flatlist|\n* Actress\n* model\n* singer\n}}\n| years_active       = 2005\u2013present\n| known_for          = \n| notable_works      = ''[[Kirarin Revolution]]'' as Kirari Tsukishima\n| height             = 166 cm\n| agent              = {{ubl|[[Up-Front Promotion]] (2005-2009)|JP Room (2009-2012, 2015-2016)|[[Oscar Promotion]] (2017-present)}}\n| module             = {{Infobox musical artist|embed=yes\n| background         = solo_singer\n| genre              = [[J-pop]]  \n| instrument         = Vocals\n| label              = [[Zetima]]\n| associated_acts    = {{flatlist|\n* [[Morning Musume]] (2005\u20132009)\n* [[Morning Musume Tanj\u014d 10nen Kinentai]]\n* [[Kira Pika]]\n* [[MilkyWay]]\n* [[ZYX (pop group)|ZYX-\u03b1]]\n* Ex-ceed!\n* [[Dream Morning Musume]] (2011\u2013Present)}}\n}}\n}}\n{{nihongo|'''Koharu Kusumi'''|\u4e45\u4f4f \u5c0f\u6625|Kusumi Koharu|born July 15, 1992 in [[Niigata Prefecture]]}} is a Japanese model, actress, [[television personality]], singer, and former voice actress. In 2005, she became the only seventh generation member of the [[Japanese idol]] [[girl group]] [[Morning Musume]], a part of [[Hello! Project]].\n\nWhile Kusumi was in Morning Musume, she provided the voice for Kirari Tsukishima, the main character of the anime series ''[[Kirarin Revolution]]'', and portrayed her in real life on ''[[Oha Suta]]''. In addition, she was featured in several musical releases affiliated with the series, including both solo releases under the name {{nihongo|Kirari Tsukishima starring Koharu Kusumi (Morning Musume)|\u6708\u5cf6\u304d\u3089\u308astarring\u4e45\u4f4f\u5c0f\u6625(\u30e2\u30fc\u30cb\u30f3\u30b0\u5a18\u3002)|}} and group releases for the units Kira Pika and Milky Way.\n\nAfter leaving Morning Musume in 2009, Kusumi pursued modeling, discussing her career changes in her 2011 autobiography, ''17-sai no Tenshoku''. After making her runway debut in 2011, she modeled exclusively for magazines ''[[CanCam]]'' and ''Steady'', while also making regular appearances on variety shows. At the same time, Kusumi continued to perform at music events and took part in [[Dream Morning Musume]]. Kusumi also ventured into acting, appearing in shows such as ''Woman Prisoner 7'' and ''[[Doctor-X: Surgeon Michiko Daimon]]''.\n\n==Early life==\nKoharu Kusumi was born in Ojimaya, [[Washima, Niigata|Washima Village]] in [[Niigata Prefecture]], and grew up in a rural neighborhood.<ref name=\"autobiography1\">{{cite book |last=Kusumi |first=Koharu |date=2011-02-12 |script-title=ja:17\u6b73\u306e\u8ee2\u8077 |url= |language=ja |location=Japan |publisher=[[Up-Front Group|Up-Front Books]] | page=212 | isbn=9784847019654 }}</ref> Her family consisted of her parents, an older sister, and an older brother.<ref name=\"autobiography1\"/> Around the middle of elementary school, Kusumi became interested in modeling from reading magazines like ''[[CanCam]]''.<ref name=\"autobiography1\"/> Prior to joining [[Morning Musume]], Kusumi was the captain of her school's [[volleyball]] team.\n\n==Career==\n\n===2005-2009: Morning Musume, ''Kirarin Revolution''===\nIn 2005, after seeing an audition call for new members for the [[Japanese idol]] group [[Morning Musume]] in a magazine, Kusumi considered applying after noticing she was eligible based on the minimum age requirements to participate.<ref name=\"autobiography1\"/> With her sister's help, Kusumi auditioned in secret with the song \"As a Person\" by [[Tomomi Kahara]].<ref name=\"autobiography1\"/> She sang \"[[Furusato (Morning Musume song)|Furusato]]\" during the final audition<ref name=\"autobiography1\"/> and was selected for the group as the only seventh generation member, a feat which earned her the nickname \"Miracle\" from producer [[Tsunku]].<ref name=\"balalaika feature\">{{cite news | author=Junko Yano | url=https://www.oricon.co.jp/music/special/061025_03.html | title=\u6708\u5cf6\u304d\u3089\u308a starring \u4e45\u4f4f\u5c0f\u6625\uff08\u30e2\u30fc\u30cb\u30f3\u30b0\u5a18\u3002\uff09\u300e\u30b9\u30fc\u30d1\u30fc\u30a2\u30a4\u30c9\u30eb\u30fb\u304d\u3089\u308a\u306e2nd\u30b7\u30f3\u30b0\u30ebPV\u5230\u7740\uff01\u300f- | language=ja | work=[[Oricon]] | date=2006-10-25 | accessdate=2018-12-27}}</ref> Kusumi debuted on the single \"[[Iroppoi Jirettai]]\" and was one of the founding members of [[Hello! Project]]'s [[kickball]] team, Metro Rabbits H.P., in 2006.\n\nIn April 2006, Kusumi was cast as the [[voice actress]] for Kirari Tsukishima, the main character in the anime ''[[Kirarin Revolution]]'' and also released music under the character's name.<ref name=\"balalaika feature\"/> Kusumi also made crossover television and concert appearances as Kirari on ''[[Haromoni@]]'' and ''[[Oha Suta]]'',<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.tv-tokyo.co.jp/contents/kirarin/news/index.html | script-title=ja:\u304a\u306f\u30b9\u30bf\u300c\u304d\u3089\u308a\u3093\u2606\u30ec\u30dc\u30ea\u30e5\u30fc\u30b7\u30e7\u30f3\u300d\u60c5\u5831\uff01\uff01 | language=ja | work=[[TV Tokyo]] | date=2008-03-31 | accessdate=2019-01-02}}</ref> leading her to become closely associated with the character.<ref name=\"balalaika feature\"/> The success of ''[[Kirarin Revolution]]'' and Kusumi's real-world appearances as Kirari made her one of the earliest examples of the \"idol voice actor\" crossover that became popular beginning in the late 2000s.<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.oricon.co.jp/news/55993/full/ | script-title=ja:\u89d2\u5ddd\u3068\u30a2\u30c3\u30d7\u30d5\u30ed\u30f3\u30c8\u304c\u30a2\u30a4\u30c9\u30eb\u58f0\u512a\u30aa\u30fc\u30c7\u30a3\u30b7\u30e7\u30f3\u958b\u50ac | language=ja | work=[[Oricon]] | date=2008-07-02 | accessdate=2018-12-28}}</ref> Throughout the show's run, Kusumi also released music as groups [[Kira Pika]] and [[MilkyWay]] with other cast members. Kusumi was named #17 in Daitan Map's \"Top 50 Voice Actors of Popular Characters\" in 2007.<ref>{{cite episode |series=\u5927\u80c6MAP\u30b9\u30da\u30b7\u30e3\u30eb\u300c\u4eba\u6c17\u30a2\u30cb\u30e1\u30ad\u30e3\u30e9\u30af\u30bf\u30fc\u306e\u58f0\u3084\u3063\u3066\u308b\u4eba\u5168\u90e8\u898b\u305b\u307e\u3059\u30d9\u30b9\u30c850\u300d |network=TV Asahi |date=2007-09-22 |language=ja}}</ref>\n\nIn early 2007, Kusumi became part of [[Morning Musume Tanj\u014d 10nen Kinentai]], a subgroup created to celebrate Morning Musume's 10th anniversary, with their first single, \"[[Bokura ga Ikiru My Asia]]\", releasing on January 24, 2007. In 2009, she released a song with the subgroup [[ZYX (pop group)|ZYX-\u03b1]].\n\nA manga adaptation by Rio Fujimi recounting Kusumi's rise to stardom was serialized in ''[[Ciao (magazine)|Ciao]]'', titled ''Miracle Revolution: Koharu Kusumi's Story''.<ref>{{cite news | first=Egan | last=Loo | url=https://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2009-05-01/an-nakahara-ends-kirarin-revolution-manga-in-japan | work=[[Anime News Network]] | date=2009-05-01 | accessdate=2020-04-05}}</ref> Preferring the freedom she had working on her solo projects, Kusumi decided to pursue a solo career after ''Kirarin Revolution'' ended,<ref name=\"autobiography1\"/> mainly in modeling<ref>{{cite web|title=To all Hello! Project Official Fanclub Members |url=https://www.up-fc.jp/helloproject/202news_kusumi.php |author=Kusumi, Koharu |publisher=Hello! Project Official Fanclub |language=Japanese |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100105154834/http://www.up-fc.jp/helloproject/202news_kusumi.php |archivedate=2010-01-05 }}</ref> as well as other paths in entertainment, including comedy.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://career.oricon.co.jp/news/70148/full/|script-title=ja:\u4e45\u4f4f\u5c0f\u6625\u3001\u30e2\u30fc\u5a18\u3002\u5352\u696d\u5f8c\u306e\u9032\u8def\u306f\u300c\u6b63\u76f4\u3001\u4e0d\u5b89\u300d|publisher=[[Oricon]]|language=Japanese|date=2009-11-01|accessdate=2010-11-08}}</ref> On September 19, 2009, [[Tsunku]] announced that Kusumi would leave Morning Musume and Hello! Project on December 6, at the final performance of Morning Musume's 2009 fall tour, ''Nine Smile''.<ref>{{cite web|title=Regarding 7th Generation Morning Musume Member \"Koharu Kusumi\" |url=https://www.up-fc.jp/helloproject/202news.php |date=2009-09-19 |publisher=Hello! Project Official Fanclub |language=Japanese |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100106005541/http://www.up-fc.jp/helloproject/202news.php |archivedate=2010-01-06 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.helloproject.com/news/0909199997_kusumi.html |script-title=ja:\u30e2\u30fc\u30cb\u30f3\u30b0\u5a18\u3002\u300c\u4e45\u4f4f\u5c0f\u6625\u300d\u306b\u95a2\u3059\u308b\u5927\u4e8b\u306a\u304a\u77e5\u3089\u305b |publisher=Hello! Project |date=2009-09-19 |accessdate=2010-11-08 |language=Japanese |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5u5SuqVWQ?url=http://www.helloproject.com/news/0909199997_kusumi.html |archivedate=November 8, 2010 }}</ref> Roughly 4,000 fans attended the graduation concert.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.barks.jp/news/?id=1000056116|script-title=ja:\u4e45\u4f4f\u5c0f\u6625\u304c\u30e2\u30fc\u30cb\u30f3\u30b0\u5a18\u3002\u3092\u5352\u696d\u3002\u6d99\u3068\u7206\u7b11\u3067\u3044\u3063\u3071\u3044\u306e\u30bb\u30ec\u30e2\u30cb\u30fc|publisher=Barks|language=Japanese|date=2009-12-07|accessdate=2010-11-08}}</ref>\n\n===2010-2015: Solo television hosting and model runway debut===\n\nAfter graduating from Morning Musume, Kusumi continued to appear on ''[[Oha Suta]]'', as well as ''Oha Coro''. In January 2010, she joined other former Morning Musume members in the group [[Dream Morning Musume]], which later debuted in April 2011.<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.barks.jp/news/?id=1000067336 | title=\u300cLOVE\u30de\u30b7\u30fc\u30f3\u300d\u73fe\u8c61\u518d\u3073\u3001\u5143\u30e2\u30fc\u30cb\u30f3\u30b0\u5a18\u3002\u30e1\u30f3\u30d0\u30fc\u306b\u3088\u308b\u5922\u306e\"\u30c9\u30ea\u30fc\u30e0 \u30e2\u30fc\u30cb\u30f3\u30b0\u5a18\u3002\" | language=ja | work=Barks | date=2010-01-31 | accessdate=2019-01-09}}</ref> In July 2010, she performed with [[Junjun (singer)|Li Chun]], [[Qian Lin]], and [[Miyabi Natsuyaki]] at the Shanghai World Expo 2010 under the group name Ex-ceed.<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.barks.jp/news/?id=1000062382 | title=EX-CEED\u3001\u77e5\u7684\u30ed\u30dc\u30c3\u30c8PALRO\u3068\u30b8\u30e7\u30a4\u30f3\u30c8 | language=ja | work=Barks | date=2010-07-02 | accessdate=2019-01-09}}</ref> \nFrom December 22\u201327, 2010, Kusumi appeared in the stage play ''Abe Naikaku'' alongside [[Natsumi Abe]] and [[Kei Yasuda]].<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.cinematoday.jp/news/N0028464 | script-title=ja:\u5b89\u500d\u306a\u3064\u307f\u300c\u5b89\u500d\u5185\u95a3\u300d\u3092\u518d\u5ea6\u767a\u8db3!?\u65e5\u672c\u521d\u306e\u5973\u6027\u9996\u76f8\u306b!?\u4fdd\u7530\u572d\u3068\u4e45\u4f4f\u5c0f\u6625\u3082\u53c2\u52a0\u3059\u308b\u30a2\u30a4\u30c9\u30eb\u653f\u6a29\uff01 | language=ja | work=Cinema Today | date=2010-11-18 | accessdate=2019-01-09}}</ref>\n\nKusumi released an autobiography titled ''17-sai no Tenshoku'' on February 12, 2011, which documented her childhood, Morning Musume, and interest in healthy lifestyles, all of which discussed her interest in pursuing a new career.<ref name=\"autobiography2\">{{cite news | url=https://www.sponichi.co.jp/entertainment/news/2011/02/18/kiji/K20110218000268630.html | script-title=ja:\u5143\u30e2\u30fc\u5a18\u3002\u4e45\u4f4f\u5c0f\u6625\u300c\u30ae\u30ea\u30ae\u30ea\u307e\u3067\u66f8\u3044\u3066\u307e\u3059\u300d  | language=ja | work=[[Sankei Sports]] | date=2011-02-18 | accessdate=2019-01-09}}</ref> She also appeared in a series of advertisements directed towards a healthy lifestyle.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://career.oricon.co.jp/news/75630/full/|script-title=ja:\u5143\u30e2\u30fc\u30cb\u30f3\u30b0\u5a18\u3002\u4e45\u4f4f\u5c0f\u6625\u3001\u4eca\u5f8c\u306f\u300c\u98df\u3068\u5065\u5eb7\u300d\u306b\u95a2\u3059\u308b\u4ed5\u4e8b\u306b\u5c31\u304f\u3053\u3068\u306b|publisher=Oricon|language=Japanese|date=2010-04-23|accessdate=2010-11-08}}</ref>\n\nIn September 2011, Kusumi made her runway debut at the [[Kobe Collection]] 2011 Autumn/Winter Show. Beginning in the same month, she modeled exclusively for the fashion magazine ''[[CanCam]]'', starting from the November 2011 issue<ref>{{cite news | url=https://mdpr.jp/news/detail/1182636 | script-title=ja:\u4e45\u4f4f\u5c0f\u6625\u3001\u30e2\u30fc\u5a18\u3002\u304b\u3089\u30e2\u30c7\u30eb\u3078\u2026\u4eca\u306e\u5fc3\u5883\u3092\u8a9e\u308b | language=ja | work=Model Press | date=2012-05-17 | accessdate=2019-01-09}}</ref><ref>{{cite news | url=https://mdpr.jp/news/detail/1403913 | title=\u300cCanCam\u300d\u4e45\u4f4f\u5c0f\u6625\u3001\u30df\u30cb\u30ef\u30f3\u30d4\u3067\u7b11\u9854\u5168\u958b\u30d5\u30a1\u30c3\u30b7\u30e7\u30f3\u30b7\u30e7\u30fc | language=ja | work=Model Press | date=2014-08-14 | accessdate=2019-01-09}}</ref>  until the September 2015 issue.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://ameblo.jp/kusumikoharu-blog/entry-12053765513.html |title=CanCam\u2661\uff5c\u4e45\u4f4f\u5c0f\u6625\u30aa\u30d5\u30a3\u30b7\u30e3\u30eb\u30d6\u30ed\u30b0\u300cKoharu\u300dPowered by Ameba |publisher=Ameblo.jp |date= |accessdate=2015-09-20}}</ref> In 2012, Kusumi made runway appearances at the ''[[CanCam]]'' \u00d7 ''[[AneCan]]'' Collaboration Fashion Show: Can Colle!,<ref>{{cite news | url=http://photo.sankei.jp.msn.com/highlight/data/2012/02/26/16cam/ | title=\u8e0a\u308b\u30d5\u30a1\u30c3\u30b7\u30e7\u30f3\u30b7\u30e7\u30fc\u3000\u300cCan\u3000\u30b3\u30ec\uff01\u300d\u3092\u524d\u306b\u3000\u30e2\u30c7\u30eb\u304c\u96c6\u5408 | language=ja | work=[[Sankei Sports]] via [[MSN]] | date=2012-02-26 | url-status=dead | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130406040903/http://photo.sankei.jp.msn.com/highlight/data/2012/02/26/16cam/ | archivedate=2013-04-06}}</ref> Stock Style 2012 Spring/Summer,<ref>{{cite news | url=https://mdpr.jp/interview/detail/1182622 | script-title=ja:\u4e45\u4f4f\u5c0f\u6625\u3001\u30b9\u30bf\u30a4\u30eb\u30ad\u30fc\u30d7\u6cd5\u30fb\u7f8e\u808c\u306e\u79d8\u8a23\u3092\u8a9e\u308b\u3000\u30e2\u30c7\u30eb\u30d7\u30ec\u30b9\u30a4\u30f3\u30bf\u30d3\u30e5\u30fc | language=ja | work=Model Press | date=2012-05-17 | accessdate=2019-01-09}}</ref> and [[Girls Award]] 2012 Autumn/Winter shows.<ref>{{cite news | url=https://mdpr.jp/news/detail/1210803 | title=\uff1c\u901f\u5831\uff1e\u300cGirls Award 2012 A\uff0fW\u300d\u306e\u6765\u5834\u8005\u6570\u767a\u8868 | language=ja | work=Model Press | date=2012-11-08 | accessdate=2019-01-09}}</ref> In 2013, she made runway appearances at the Girls Award 2013 Spring/Summer,<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.crank-in.net/interview/23881 | title=\u5143\u30fb\u30e2\u30fc\u5a18\u3002\u4e45\u4f4f\u5c0f\u6625\u304c\u30e9\u30f3\u30a6\u30a7\u30a4\u306b\u30ad\u30e9\u30ea\u7b11\u9854\u3067\u767b\u5834\uff01\uff1cGirlsAward 2013 \u6625\u590f\uff1e | language=ja | work=Crank In | date=2013-03-23 | accessdate=2019-01-09}}</ref> [[Tokyo Girls Collection]] 2013 Spring Live, ReaMa Pastel Party 2013 in Tokyo Show,<ref>{{cite news | url=https://mdpr.jp/fashion/detail/1240920 | title=AKB48\u6cb3\u897f\u667a\u7f8e\u306e\u7f8e\u4eba\u59c9\u3082\u767b\u5834\u3000\u4e45\u4f4f\u5c0f\u6625\u3001\u30e9\u30d6\u30ea\u304c\u83ef\u3084\u304b\u30e9\u30f3\u30a6\u30a7\u30a4\uff1c\u5199\u771f\u7279\u96c6\uff1e | language=ja | work=Model Press | date=2013-04-30 | accessdate=2019-01-09}}</ref> and Girls Award 2013 Autumn/Winter shows.<ref>{{cite news | url=https://mdpr.jp/fashion/detail/1283075 | title=\u5016\u7530\u4f86\u672a\u3001\u65b0\u57a3\u7d50\u8863\u3001\u5c71\u7530\u512a\u3001\u83dc\u3005\u7dd2\u3089\u8c6a\u83ef\u51fa\u6f14\u8005\u304c\u7af6\u6f14\u300cGirlsAward 2013 A\uff0fW\u300d\uff1c\u5199\u771f\u7279\u96c6\uff1e | language=ja | work=Model Press | date=2013-09-28 | accessdate=2019-01-09}}</ref>\n\nIn 2014, Kusumi left ''[[Oha Suta]]'' and later hosted ''Blurred Sound Pops'' until 2015.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.asahi.com/and_M/interest/entertainment/Cfettp01509150055.html |title=\u3008\u901f\u5831\u3009\uff4d\uff49\uff53\uff4f\uff4e\uff4f\u300c\u6795\u55b6\u696d\u3057\u3066\u307e\u305b\u3093\u304b\u3089\u300d\u552f\u4e00\u7d99\u7d9a\u51fa\u6f14 - \u65e5\u520a\u30b9\u30dd\u30fc\u30c4\u82b8\u80fd\u901f\u5831 - \u671d\u65e5\u65b0\u805e\u30c7\u30b8\u30bf\u30eb\uff06\uff2d |publisher=Asahi.com |date=2015-09-15 |accessdate=2015-09-20}}</ref> She also starred in two live-action dramas, ''Inauguration! Girl's Cabinet'', and ''Again!!''.\n\nIn May 2015, Kusumi became a host of \"Boat Race Live.\" on  BS Fuji.<ref>http://ameblo.jp/kusumikoharu-blog/entry-12026526721.html</ref>\n\nIn November 2015. Kusumi started working as a model for the fashion magazine \"steady.\"  <ref>http://ameblo.jp/kusumikoharu-blog/entry-12095566758.html</ref>\n\n===2016-present: Venture into acting===\n\nOn January 9. 2016. Kusumi started hosting a weekly radio show called \"This Happy Time (or KoHappy Time).\"<ref>https://www.fmport.com/program/index.html?key=af087cba5b3a46abab4294d77d7dae30.  Retrieved 2016-01-22</ref> On April 1, 2016, Kusumi started hosting a second radio program called \"Kusumi Koharu's Mediaship 927\" on BSN also in Niigata, Japan.<ref name=\"ohbsn.com\">http://www.ohbsn.com/radio/programs/koharu/ {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160426102020/http://www.ohbsn.com/radio/programs/koharu/ |date=2016-04-26 }} Retrieved 2016-04-23</ref>\n\nOn November 29, 2016, Kusumi announced that her contract with her talent agency, JP Room, would end on November 30.<ref>http://www.oricon.co.jp/news/2082242/full/</ref> In early 2017 it was announced that Kusumi would be represented by [[Oscar Promotion]], and would have a role as geisha in a drama called \"Woman Prisoner 7.\"  <ref>http://www.oricon.co.jp/news/2088829/full/</ref>\n\nIn October 2017, Kusumi appeared in the fifth season of the popular medical drama, [[Doctor-X]] as Nurse Haruna Nagamori.<ref name=\"tv-asahi.co.jp\">http://www.tv-asahi.co.jp/doctor-x/cast/</ref>\n\nOn November 23, 2018, Kusumi appeared in a supporting role in the feature film, \"Lady in White.\"\n\n== Discography ==\n{{For|releases with Morning Musume|Morning Musume discography}}\n\n===As Kirari Tsukishima===\n{{Main|Kirarin Revolution discography}}\n\n{{col-begin}}\n{{col-2}}\n;Studio albums\n* ''[[Mitsuboshi]]'' (2006)\n* ''[[Kirarin Land]]'' (2007)\n* ''[[Kirari to Fuyu]]'' (2008)\n\n;Compilation albums\n* ''[[Best Kirari]]'' (2009)\n{{col-2}}\n\n;Singles\n* \"[[Koi Kana]]\" (2006)\n* \"[[Balalaika (song)|Balalaika]]\" (2006)\n* \"[[Happy (Kirarin Revolution song)|Happy]]\" (2007)\n* \"[[Chance! (Kirarin Revolution song)|Chance!]]\" (2007)\n* \"[[Papancake]]\" (2008)\n* \"[[Happy Happy Sunday!]]\" (2009)\n{{col-end}}\n\n==Publications==\n\n=== Photobooks ===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n! Year\n! Title<ref name=\"helloproject1\">{{cite web|url=http://www.helloproject.com/schedule/01/01/list03.html |title=Hello! Project photobook release schedule |accessdate=January 16, 2009 |publisher=Hello! Project |language=Japanese |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070120145705/http://www.helloproject.com/schedule/01/01/list03.html |archivedate=January 20, 2007 }}</ref>\n! Publisher\n! ISBN\n|-\n| 2006\n| {{nihongo|''Koharu Kusumi''|\u4e45\u4f4f\u5c0f\u6625|}}\n| Wani Books\n|{{ISBN|978-4-8470-2923-3}}\n|- \n| 2007\n| Pop\n| [[Kadokawa Shoten|Kadokawa]]\n| {{ISBN|978-4-04-894499-1}}\n|- \n| rowspan=\"2\" | 2008\n| {{nihongo|''Koharu Nikki''|\u4e45\u4f4f\u5c0f\u6625\u5199\u771f\u96c6\u300c\u5c0f\u6625\u65e5\u8a18\u3002\u300d}}\n| Wani Books\n| {{ISBN|978-4-8470-4102-0}}\n|- \n| {{Nihongo|''Happy Memorial Photobook''|\u6708\u5cf6\u304d\u3089\u308a\u3000starring \u4e45\u4f4f\u5c0f\u6625(\u30e2\u30fc\u30cb\u30f3\u30b0\u5a18\u3002)\u300e\u30cf\u30c3\u30d4\u30fc\u30e1\u30e2\u30ea\u30a2\u30eb\u2606\u30d5\u30a9\u30c8\u30d6\u30c3\u30af}} <br>{{small|(''[[Kirarin Revolution]]''; credited as Kirari Tsukishima starring Koharu Kusumi (Morning Musume))}}\n| [[Shogakukan]]\n| {{ISBN|978-4-09-132290-6}}\n|- \n| 2009\n| ''Sugar Doll''\n| Wani Books\n| {{ISBN|978-4-8470-4202-7}}\n|- \n| 2017\n| ''Moment''\n| [[Futabasha]]\n| {{ISBN|978-4-5753-1321-5}}\n|-\n|}\n\n=== Autobiographies ===\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n! Year\n! Title<ref name=\"helloproject1\"/>\n! Publisher\n! ISBN\n|-\n| 2011\n| {{nihongo|''17-sai no Tenshoku''|17\u6b73\u306e\u8ee2\u8077}}\n| Up-Front Books\n| {{ISBN|978-4-8470-1965-4}}\n|-\n|}\n\n== Filmography ==\n\n=== Television===\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Title\n! Role\n! Network\n! Notes\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\" | 2005\n| ''[[Hello! Morning]]''\n| Herself\n| rowspan=\"6\"| [[TV Tokyo]]\n| [[Morning Musume]]'s variety show\n|-\n| {{nihongo|''Musume Dokyu!''|\u5a18DOKYU!}}\n| Herself\n| [[Morning Musume]]'s variety show\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\" | 2006\n| ''[[Kirarin Revolution]]''\n| Kirari Tsukishima\n| Voice; lead role\n|-\n| ''[[Oha Suta]]''\n| [[